const a = [
  {"id":3494,"text":"What is the most specific marker for myocardial infarction?","explanation":"**Troponin-I** is a **highly specific and sensitive marker** for myocardial infarction. It rises within 3-12 hours following the onset of symptoms and can remain elevated for up to 10-14 days, making it useful for both early diagnosis and late presentation.\r\n\r\n\r\nCreatine phosphokinase-MB (CK-MB) is an older marker and is not as specific as troponin-I. It can be elevated in conditions like skeletal muscle injury.\r\n\r\nCreatine phosphokinase-BB (CK-BB) is predominantly found in the brain and is not specific for cardiac tissue.\r\n\r\nAlkaline phosphatase is not a marker for myocardial infarction; it is more relevant for liver and bone pathology.\r\n\r\nLactate dehydrogenase (LDH or LD) is also less specific for myocardial infarction and can be elevated in many other conditions such as hemolysis, liver disease, and some cancers.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 74.","responses":[{"text":"Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH or LD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin-I","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatine phosphokinase-BB (CK-BB)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatine phosphokinase-MB (CK-MB)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3537,"text":"A continuous, \"machine-like\" murmur is associated with what congenital pathology?","explanation":"A **patent ductus arteriosus** presents with a characteristic **\"machine-like\" murmur**, usually **continuous** in nature. The murmur results from a continuous shunt of blood between the aorta and the pulmonary artery, bypassing the lungs.\r\n\r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot usually presents with a harsh systolic murmur due to pulmonic stenosis.\r\n\r\nCoarctation of the aorta generally causes a systolic murmur best heard on the back, but it is not continuous or \"machine-like.\"\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect (ASD) produces a systolic ejection murmur but does not have the \"machine-like\" quality.\r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect (VSD) generally causes a holosystolic murmur, not a continuous one.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Teratology of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3545,"text":"Which cardiac dysfunction is seen in restrictive cardiomyopathy?","explanation":"In **restrictive cardiomyopathy**, the primary issue is impaired filling of the heart during diastole due to increased stiffness of the ventricular walls. There's limited ventricular stretch and impaired relaxation, causing **diastolic dysfunction**. Systolic function is often preserved until late in the disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 570.","responses":[{"text":"Systolic dysfunction that converts to diastolic with increasing severity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systolic dysfunction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has no effect on systolic or diastolic function of heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diastolic dysfunction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Both systolic and diastolic dysfunction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3597,"text":"A 2-year-old baby had congenital heart disease. Which syndrome is most commonly associated with congenital heart disease?","explanation":"**Down syndrome** is frequently associated with **congenital heart defects**, specifically atrioventricular septal defects. Nearly half of all children with Down syndrome have some form of congenital heart disease, making it the most common syndrome associated with such defects.\r\n\r\n\r\nKlinefelter syndrome is a chromosomal disorder, but it is not primarily associated with congenital heart disease.\r\n\r\nAlthough maternal rubella infection can lead to congenital heart disease, it is not a syndrome associated with a high frequency of such defects.\r\n\r\nWhile DiGeorge syndrome: syndrome can include heart defects, it is not as commonly associated with congenital heart disease as Down syndrome.","reference":"Cardiovascular module, Medicine lecture slides, Topic: A practical approach to congenital heart diseases, Subtopic: Risk factors.","responses":[{"text":"DiGeorge syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klinefelter syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Down syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3601,"text":"'Sign of 3' is a feature of which congenital disease of the heart?","explanation":"In **coarctation of the aorta**, classic radiographic findings can include a **\"3 sign\"** or \"figure 3 sign,\" which is due to pre- and post-stenotic dilatation of the aorta and indentation at the site of coarctation. This is often seen on a chest X-ray and can help in the diagnosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot is characterized on the chest X-ray as a \"boot-shaped\" heart, not the \"3 sign.\"\r\nPersistent truncus arteriosus involves a single arterial vessel coming out of the heart and does not produce a \"3 sign\" on imaging.\r\nAtrial septal defect and patent ductus arteriosus do have any specific radiographic findings.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 534.","responses":[{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent truncus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3609,"text":"A 30-year-old patient is identified with hypertension in his upper extremities and hypotension in his lower extremities. His X-ray shows notches on his ribs. What is the most likely condition ssociated with his presentations?","explanation":"**Coarctation of the aorta** is characterized by a narrowing of the aorta, which leads to a pressure gradient above and below the site of narrowing. This results in increased blood pressure in the upper extremities and decreased pressure in the lower extremities. **Rib notching** is due to collateral circulation that develops to bypass the narrow segment, causing erosion of the inferior aspect of the ribs.\r\n\r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot typically presents with cyanosis and a \"boot-shaped\" heart on X-ray, not with differential blood pressures in the upper and lower extremities.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect involves an opening between the atria and usually presents with signs of right-sided heart overload, not the symptoms described.\r\n\r\nInfundibular pulmonary stenosis causes obstruction between the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery but would not cause the symptoms described.\r\n\r\nPatent ductus arteriosus involves a duct between the aorta and the pulmonary artery remaining open after birth, leading to a \"machinery\" murmur and potential heart failure but not the symptoms described.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 78.","responses":[{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of the aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibular pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3694,"text":"What is the name of the point which adjoins the QRS complex and the ST segment?","explanation":"The **J point** is the junction of the termination of the QRS complex and the beginning of the ST segment on the electrocardiogram (ECG). It's important in diagnosing and assessing various cardiac conditions, including myocardial infarctions and various types of cardiac arrhythmias.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 153.","responses":[{"text":"J point","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X descent point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C wave point","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3809,"text":"Which of the following findings would indicate a high-risk factor prediction while performing the exercise tolerance test (ETT)?","explanation":"**ST-segment depression of 2 mm or more in inferior leads** during exercise tolerance testing is considered a strong indicator of myocardial ischemia and is a **high-risk factor for coronary artery disease**. This finding typically warrants further diagnostic investigations and possibly therapeutic interventions.\r\n\r\n\r\nA small drop in diastolic blood pressure is usually not considered a high-risk factor during ETT.\r\n\r\nUpsloping ST depressions are generally considered to be less specific for ischemia than horizontal or downsloping ST depressions.\r\n\r\nA drop in systolic BP could be concerning, but a 5 mm Hg drop is usually not considered a high-risk feature.\r\n\r\n ST elevation can be a concerning sign, but it usually needs to be evaluated in the context of other clinical and ECG findings. Isolated 1 mm ST elevation in V2-V6 without other corroborating evidence is not usually considered a high-risk factor prediction in ETT.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 449.","responses":[{"text":"2 mm ST depression in inferior leads","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3 mm Hg drop in diastolic blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 mm ST elevation in V2-V6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upsloping ST depression of 3 mm in V2-V6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 mm Hg drop in systolic blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3854,"text":"A patient taking a class of antihypertensives complains about side effects of severe dry cough. Which of the following drugs is causing the dry cough?","explanation":"**Captopril** belongs to the class of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, which are well-known for causing a **persistent dry cough** as a side effect. This cough can be severe enough to warrant discontinuation of the medication, and it typically resolves after stopping the drug.\r\n\r\n\r\nPropanolol and atenolol are beta-blockers and are generally not associated with causing a dry cough.\r\n\r\nVerapamil and diltiazem are calcium channel blockers and usually cause constipation as a side effect.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 187-188, 210.","responses":[{"text":"Diltiazem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Verapamil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propanolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3864,"text":"Which of the following correctly defines idiosyncrasy?","explanation":"**Idiosyncratic** reactions are **unpredictable** and **not dose-dependent**. They are **rare** adverse effects that occur **sporadically** among the population, often even at low dosages. These reactions are usually due to genetic differences in metabolism or immune response and are difficult to foresee.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\nWidespread allergic response is an exaggerated immune reaction to a drug but is not idiosyncratic.\r\n\r\nAdverse effects that generally occur in the majority of the population would be common side effects, not idiosyncrasies.\r\n\r\nAn exaggerated immune response can be an allergic reaction but is not specifically what is meant by idiosyncrasy.","reference":"Uetrecht J, Naisbitt DJ. Idiosyncratic adverse drug reactions: current concepts. Pharmacological Reviews. Published April 2013. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3639727/","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adverse effects that are infrequent and sporadically seen among the population even with low dosages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Widespread allergic response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exaggerated immune response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adverse effects that generally occur in the majority of population","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3890,"text":"Which of the following is a side effect of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors?","explanation":null,"reference":"Goyal A, Cusick AS, Thielemier B. Ace inhibitors. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 15, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430896/","responses":[{"text":"Agranulocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal artery stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3892,"text":"Which vasculitis involves the aorta?","explanation":"**Takayasu disease**, also known as Takayasu arteritis, predominantly affects **large vessels**, including the **aorta and its main branches**. It is most commonly seen in young women and can lead to symptoms such as arm claudication, decreased pulses, and vascular bruits.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPolyarteritis nodosa typically involves medium-sized arteries and does not generally affect the aorta.\r\n\r\nBehcet disease is a multisystem vasculitis but does not primarily involve the aorta.\r\n\r\nGiant cell arteritis affects large and medium-sized vessels, such as the temporal artery, but it generally does not involve the aorta.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 65.","responses":[{"text":"Behcet disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyarteritis nodosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Takayasu disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3902,"text":"In which of the following is the sinoatrial node present?","explanation":"The **sinoatrial (SA) node** is located in the **right atrium** near the entrance of the superior vena cava. It serves as the primary pacemaker of the heart, initiating the electrical impulses that set the rate and rhythm of cardiac contractions.","reference":"Kashou AH, Basit H, Chhabra L. Physiology, sinoatrial node. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459238/","responses":[{"text":"Left ventricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right atrium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left atrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3903,"text":"A 46-year-old woman suffering from obesity is traveling from Pakistan to USA. She starts experiencing shortness of breath. Which of the following could be a likely reason?","explanation":"**Pulmonary embolism** is a common and potentially fatal condition. In the context of a **long flight** (prolonged immobility) and **obesity** (both risk factors for deep vein thrombosis and subsequent pulmonary embolism), the symptoms of acute shortness of breath would most likely point towards a pulmonary embolism.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAAlthough severe, aortic dissection is generally characterized by intense tearing pain in the chest or back rather than isolated shortness of breath. It is also less likely than a pulmonary embolism in the context of long travel and obesity.\r\n\r\nPericarditis usually causes chest pain that is relieved by sitting forward, and is less likely to present acutely with shortness of breath alone in an otherwise asymptomatic person.\r\n\r\nAcute coronary syndrome rypically presents with chest pain, pressure, or discomfort rather than isolated shortness of breath. Also, it is less likely in the context of her travel history.\r\nHyperlipidemia is a chronic condition that wouldn't cause acute symptoms like shortness of breath.","reference":"1) Innes JA, Dover AR, Fairhurst K, Macleod J, eds. Macleod’s Clinical Examination. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 42.\r\n\r\n2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 558.\r\n\r\n\r\n3) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 698.","responses":[{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute coronary syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperlipidemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3911,"text":"Which of the following leads to constrictive cardiomyopathy in transfusion dependent thalassemia?","explanation":"**Hemochromatosis** occurs due to iron overload, which is a common complication in transfusion-dependent thalassemia patients. The excess iron deposits in various tissues, including the heart, leading to fibrosis and subsequently, **constrictive cardiomyopathy**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAnemia is indeed a feature of thalassemia but is not the direct cause of constrictive cardiomyopathy in this context.\r\n\r\nHypoxia, or lack of oxygen, could be a result of severe anemia or other conditions, but it is not the direct cause of constrictive cardiomyopathy in transfusion-dependent thalassemia.\r\n\r\nTachycardia refers to a fast heart rate and is not the direct cause of constrictive cardiomyopathy.\r\n\r\nWhile hemolysis may be a feature of thalassemia, it is not the cause of constrictive cardiomyopathy in this situation.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 318.","responses":[{"text":"Hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemochromatosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3961,"text":"Peripheral cyanosis occurs in which of the following pathologies?","explanation":"**Low cardiac output** can result in **peripheral cyanosis** due to inadequate blood circulation, causing a lack of oxygen supply to the extremities. When the body's tissues and organs do not receive enough oxygen, they may exhibit a bluish color, known as cyanosis.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCongenital heart diseases (right to left shunt condition would more likely result in central cyanosis, affecting areas like the lips and tongue, rather than peripheral cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary edema condition primarily affects lung function and would generally lead to central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary embolism would primarily affect lung function and would typically result in central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nLung diseases would generally result in central cyanosis due to impaired gas exchange in the lungs, affecting the oxygen saturation of blood circulating to the central parts of the body.","reference":"Adeyinka A, Kondamudi NP. Cyanosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482247/","responses":[{"text":"Lung diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low cardiac output","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital heart diseases (right to left shunt)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3998,"text":"Oligemic lung fields on X-ray chest are seen in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"**Tetralogy of Fallot** is a congenital heart defect characterized by four anatomical abnormalities, including ventricular septal defect, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and an overriding aorta. Due to these abnormalities,, there is a decrease in the blood flow to the lungs, leading to **decreased vascularity** or **\"oligemic\"** lung fields on a chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nTricuspid regurgitation primarily affects the right atrium and right ventricle and does not typically cause oligemic lung fields on chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect results in a left-to-right shunt and would not be expected to produce oligemic lung fields.\r\n\r\nMitral stenosis mainly affects the left atrium and left ventricle and tends to cause pulmonary congestion, not oligemia.\r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect generally causes increased blood flow to the lungs due to a left-to-right shunt, which would not produce oligemic lung fields.","reference":"Weerakkody Y. Tetralogy of fallot | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. doi:10.53347/rID-7356","responses":[{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4002,"text":"Anticoagulants are given after which of the following mitral valve surgeries?","explanation":"**Anticoagulants** are usually required after **mechanical valve replacement** to prevent thromboembolic complications. Mechanical valves have a higher propensity for clot formation due to their synthetic material, so **lifelong anticoagulation therapy** is often recommended to minimize this risk.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 524.","responses":[{"text":"Balloon valvuloplasty","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bioprosthetic valve replacement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mechanical valve replacement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of them","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transcatheter Aortic Valve Replacement (TAVR)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4029,"text":"What amount of charcoal is required as an antidote?","explanation":"**Activated charcoal** is used in the management of poisoning, typically within one hour of the ingestion of a toxic substance. It works by binding to the toxin in the gastrointestinal tract, thus reducing its absorption into the systemic circulation. In adults, the general dose of activated charcoal is **60-100 gm**.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 475.","responses":[{"text":"2-4 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100-200 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15-30 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5-10 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"60-100 gm","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4051,"text":"Which of the following is the gold standard test for diagnosing coronary artery disease?","explanation":"**Coronary angiography** is considered the gold standard for diagnosing **coronary artery disease (CAD)**. It involves the injection of contrast dye into the coronary arteries via a catheter, allowing for direct visualization of the vessels and any blockages or stenosis. This method is highly sensitive and specific and allows for both diagnostic and therapeutic interventions, such as angioplasty or stent placement.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAlthough cardiac magnetic resonance imaging provides valuable anatomical and functional data, it is generally not used as the primary diagnostic tool for CAD.\r\n\r\nExercise tolerance testing (ETT) is useful for risk stratification and evaluation of ischemia but is not as accurate or definitive as coronary angiography.\r\n\r\nStress echocardiography is used to assess for inducible ischemia, but lacks the specificity and sensitivity of coronary angiography.\r\n\r\nWhile cardiac CT can visualize coronary anatomy and assess for the presence of coronary artery calcium, it is not as sensitive or specific as coronary angiography for the detection of significant CAD.","reference":"Shahjehan RD, Bhutta BS. Coronary artery disease. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564304/","responses":[{"text":"Stress echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"High-resolution CT-scanning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise tolerance testing (ETT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4053,"text":"A term infant is born with a large ventricular septal defect (VSD). Which congenital heart disease is most commonly associated with VSD?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teratology of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4097,"text":"A 45-year-old man presents to the clinic because of tingling or numbness in the hands along with pain in his extremities. He has a 20-pack year history of smoking and is finally diagnosed with vasculitis involving medium and small arteries with veins. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Buerger's disease**, also known as thromboangiitis obliterans, predominantly affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins. It is more commonly observed in **smokers** and is characterized by symptoms like tingling, numbness, and pain in the extremities.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGranulomatosis with polyangitis primarily involves the respiratory tract and kidneys and is less likely to present with symptoms in the extremities. \r\n\r\nChurg Strauss syndrome is associated with asthma and eosinophilia and mainly affects the lungs and skin. \r\n\r\nGiant cell arteritis usually affects older people and is commonly seen involving the temporal artery, presenting with symptoms like headaches and vision issues. \r\n\r\nPolyarteritis nodosa is a systemic form of vasculitis affecting multiple organs but is not specifically associated with smoking.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 512.","responses":[{"text":"Buerger's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatosis with polyangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Churg Strauss syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyarteritis nodosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4130,"text":"Which one of the following is true about diastolic heart sounds?","explanation":"Mitral stenosis usually results in a **diastolic murmur** that is heard best at the apex of the heart. This murmur is often described as a long or **holodiastolic rumbling** and is indicative of severe mitral stenosis. It is often best heard in the left lateral decubitus position with the bell of the stethoscope.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTricuspid regurgitation actually produces a pansystolic murmur rather than a holodiastolic one, typically heard best at the left lower sternal border. Acute severe aortic regurgitation (AR) usually produces an early diastolic decrescendo murmur, not a late diastolic murmur. Mitral valve prolapse (MVP) is usually associated with a midsystolic click and a late systolic murmur rather than a diastolic murmur. Tricuspid stenosis does indeed produce a diastolic murmur; it is a diastolic rumbling murmur heard best in the left lower sternal border and increases in intensity during inspiration.","reference":"Penman, Ian D., et al. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed., Elsevier, 2022: 460, 518-519.","responses":[{"text":"A long or holodiastolic rumbling is indicative of severe mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis does not produce any diastolic sounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation produce holodiastolic murmur at 4th intercostal space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MVP usually produces early diastolic murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute severe AR produce late diastolic murmur at apex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4142,"text":"A 42-year-old man comes to the emergency department with a history of taking liquids for suicide purpose. His pulse rate is 92/min and blood pressure is 120 /70 mmhg. He also has ulceration around the mouth and tongue. His chest is full of crepts and has severely labored breathing. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","explanation":"In a case of suspected poisoning leading to severe respiratory distress and potential airway compromise, the primary objective is to stabilize the patient's vital functions. This includes **establishing and maintaining the airway**, **supporting breathing**, and **ensuring adequate circulation** (often referred to as **ABCs**). These basic life-supporting measures are of utmost importance and take precedence over other treatment modalities. In a case like this, the patient may require intubation or other advanced airway management techniques, supplemental oxygen, and possibly intravenous fluids and medications to support blood pressure and heart function.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nMouth wash and antacids may be helpful for treating the ulcerations around the mouth and tongue but do not address the primary life-threatening issues of airway compromise and respiratory distress. Maintaining blood pressure is important but is part of the 'C' in ABC and should not take precedence over airway and breathing. Injection morphine could potentially worsen respiratory depression and is not appropriate in this context. Airway maintenance alone does not address the need for ensuring adequate breathing and circulation.","reference":"Thim T, Krarup NHV, Grove EL, Rohde CV, Løfgren B. Initial assessment and treatment with the airway, breathing, circulation, disability, exposure (ABCDE) approach. International Journal of General Medicine. Published January 31, 2012. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3273374/","responses":[{"text":"Mouth wash and antacids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway, breathing and circulation establishment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood pressure maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Injection morphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4146,"text":"Which type of atrial septal defect (ASD) is commonly associated with atrioventricular (AV) canal defect?","explanation":"**ASD primum** is commonly associated with **atrioventricular (AV) canal defects**. This is often seen in conditions like Down syndrome and is part of the spectrum of atrioventricular septal defects, which involve both the atrial and the ventricular septum as well as one or both of the AV valves.\r\n\r\nASD secundum is the most common type of ASD but is not specifically associated with AV canal defects. ASD sinus venosus and ASD coronary sinus are also specific types of ASD but are not commonly linked with AV canal defects.","reference":"Umapathi KK, Agasthi P. Atrioventricular canal defects. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557511/","responses":[{"text":"ASD secundum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD primum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD sinus venosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD coronary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4152,"text":"On autopsy, internal aspects of the stomach show brown folds and hardened esophagus. The acid involved will be:","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 487.\r\n2. Dow lecture slides: Cardiovascular module, Forensic slides, Topic: Corrosive poisoning 2","responses":[{"text":"Salicylic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4157,"text":"A 25-year-old man complains of sharp pain which increases on lying down and is relieved with sitting. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Pericarditis** is characterized by sharp chest pain that often worsens when lying down and improves upon sitting up or leaning forward. This pattern is due to the inflammation of the pericardial sac surrounding the heart.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAortic dissection generally presents with severe, tearing pain that often radiates to the back. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) would be less likely to cause acute, sharp chest pain and is usually associated with long-term symptoms like shortness of breath and chronic cough. Both ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) would cause ischemic chest pain but generally would not have pain characteristics that change with position. They would also likely have other symptoms such as radiating pain, sweating, and palpitations.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 542.","responses":[{"text":"ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4162,"text":"Acid neutralization within the stomach, in case of sulphuric acid ingestion, is contraindicated by which of the following?","explanation":"Acid neutralization within the stomach, in case of sulphuric acid ingestion, is contraindicated by **sodium bicarbonate**, when used to neutralize sulfuric acid, may produce excessive gas and result in gastric distension. This could increase the risk of gastric perforation.\r\n\r\nAluminum hydroxide gel, milk products, egg white, and milk of magnesia are generally used for acid neutralization in the stomach, although the effectiveness of these substances is not universally accepted for treating acid ingestion.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 484.","responses":[{"text":"Egg white","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Milk of magnesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide gel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Milk products","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4168,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by normal plasma B type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels?","explanation":"In **constrictive pericarditis**, the heart's ability to stretch and fill with blood is impaired due to a rigid pericardium. Despite this, the myocardium itself is not usually dysfunctional in the way it is in cardiomyopathies. **BNP** is typically released from **ventricular myocardium** under conditions of stress and stretch, which is less commonly seen in constrictive pericarditis compared to other listed conditions. Therefore, BNP levels are more likely to be normal in this case.\r\n---\r\n\r\nEndomyocardial arbitrative cardiomyopathy, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, dilated cardiomyopathy, and restrictive cardiomyopathy are conditions that affect the myocardium itself and are often associated with elevated BNP levels due to myocardial stress and stretch.","reference":"(1) Novack ML, Zevitz ME. Natriuretic peptide b type test. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556136/\r\n(2) Parakh N, Mehrotra S, Seth S, et al. NT pro B type natriuretic peptide levels in constrictive pericarditis and restrictive cardiomyopathy. Indian Heart Journal. Published 2015. Accessed June 26, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4382553/","responses":[{"text":"Constrictive pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endomyocardial arbitrative cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4172,"text":"Which one of the following tests (non-invasive) has the highest sensitivity in detecting coronary artery disease?","explanation":"**CT angiography** (computed tomography angiography) provides high-resolution images and is highly sensitive for detecting **coronary artery disease**. It allows visualization of coronary arteries and assessment of coronary artery disease with a high level of detail. It is especially useful for ruling out CAD in patients with low to intermediate risk.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nExercise tolerance test (ETT) is useful for risk stratification but not as sensitive as CT angiography for detecting CAD.\r\n\r\nStress echocardiography is useful for assessing functional impact but less sensitive than CT angiography.\r\n\r\nThallium scan is used in the assessment but not as sensitive as CT angiography.\r\n\r\nCardiac MRI is highly sensitive and specific but less commonly used than CT angiography due to cost and availability.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 452.","responses":[{"text":"CT angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise tolerance test (ETT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thallium scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stress echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac MRI","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4176,"text":"Which one of the following is correct regarding mitral stenosis (MS)?","explanation":"In **mitral stenosis**, the obstruction at the mitral valve causes turbulent flow across the valve during diastole, generating a **mid-diastolic rumbling murmur** that is best heard over the cardiac apex with the bell of the stethoscope.\r\n\r\nUsually, the symptoms of mitral stenosis occur when the mitral valve area reduces to about 1.5 cm^2 or less.\r\n\r\nMitral balloon valvotomy is not recommended for heavily calcified valves due to risk of complications.\r\n\r\nAntibiotic prophylaxis against infective endocarditis is only recommended in certain conditions or procedures.\r\n\r\nMS is commonly a result of rheumatic heart disease, although congenital forms do exist.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"It is mostly congenital in origin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The patient remains asymptomatic until the valve area is less than 1 cm^2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotic prophylaxis against infective endocarditis is given to all patients","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turbulent flow produces the characteristic low pitched mid diastolic murmur","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral balloon valvotomy can be safely done in patients with heavily calcified mitral valve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4177,"text":"Which of the following factors has an association with congenital heart disease?","explanation":"Maternal infection with **rubella virus** during pregnancy, especially in the first trimester, can lead to a range of congenital abnormalities, including congenital heart disease in the newborn, i.e., **patent ductus arteriosus (PDA)**.\r\n\r\nThere is no established scientific evidence linking maternal tea consumption to congenital heart disease.\r\nOccupation: Occupation alone is generally not considered a risk factor for congenital heart disease.\r\nWhile maternal hypertension may have other adverse fetal effects, it is not directly associated with congenital heart diseases.\r\n\r\nWhile hypoxia can affect the fetus in multiple ways, it is not a known specific risk factor for congenital heart disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occupation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Use of tea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella infection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4187,"text":"A 25-year-old patient with difficulty in breathing is diagnosed to have congestive heart failure. He is found to have differences in right and left arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses and notching of ribs on X-ray. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Coarctation of the aorta** is characterized by a narrowing of the aorta and would account for the symptoms of congestive heart failure, as well as the **differences in arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses**, and **rib notching on X-ray**.\r\n\r\nTransposition of great vessels typically causes cyanotic disease in the newborn period and is unlikely to present in this age group.\r\n\r\nMitral valve stenosis primarily affects the left heart and does not usually cause differences in arm pulses or diminished femoral pulses. \r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect would not lead to diminished femoral pulses or differences in right and left arm pulses. \r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot, a cyanotic congenital heart disease, would have been likely diagnosed much earlier in life and also does not typically present with rib notching or pulse differences between the arms.","reference":"1. Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 78.\r\n2. Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 509, 534.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral valve stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4224,"text":"Which of the following examination findings would most likely be seen in a patient with aortic stenosis?","explanation":"**Aortic stenosis** is characterized by a **diamond-shaped ejection murmur**. This type of murmur occurs during systole and is a **crescendo-decrescendo** type, typically loudest at the right second intercostal space or right upper sternal border and radiating to the carotid arteries. It often produces a palpable thrill. The murmur can actually become softer with increasing severity.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 522 (Fig 16.84).","responses":[{"text":"Diamond shaped ejection murmur","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No thrill","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intensity of murmur directly related to the severity of the lesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Murmur loudest along left sternal border","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extremely long decrescendo murmur","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4246,"text":"Which of the following conditions is characterized by a sustained apex impulse?","explanation":"In **aortic stenosis**, the apex impulse is often **sustained** due to the prolonged ejection of blood from the left ventricle, which is working harder to overcome the obstruction at the aortic valve.\r\n\r\nSustained apex impulse is not a feature typically seen in patent ductus arteriosus, Ventricular septal defects, hyperdynamic states, or mitral stenosis. In these conditions, other physical exam findings may be more prominent. For instance, hyperdynamic states usually present with a bounding pulse rather than a sustained apex impulse. Mitral stenosis would typically show a tapping apex due to the palpable first heart sound.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyper dynamic states","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10213,"text":"A researcher wants to establish the prevalence of tuberculosis in Karachi. Which study design is most suitable for this?","explanation":"A **cross-sectional study** would be the most suitable study design for establishing the **prevalence of tuberculosis** in Karachi. This type of study is designed to assess the prevalence of a disease or condition in a specific population at a given point in time.\r\n\r\nCohort studies are usually forward-looking and are not the best to determine prevalence at a specific point. Case reports and case series are descriptive studies focused on single or multiple cases, but they do not provide a measure of prevalence. Case-control studies are retrospective and designed to identify factors associated with a disease, rather than determining its prevalence.","reference":"Jesson J. Cross-sectional studies in prescribing research. Published December 2001. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11722676/","responses":[{"text":"Cross-sectional study","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10251,"text":"What is the most common type of cardiomyopathy?","explanation":"**Dilated cardiomyopathy** is the most common type of cardiomyopathy. This form is characterized by enlargement and weakening of the heart's ventricular chambers, which can lead to heart failure and other complications.\r\n\r\nHypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the second most common and is characterized by thickening of the heart muscle, specifically the ventricular walls. Restrictive cardiomyopathy is the least common and involves the stiffening of the ventricular walls. Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia is a rare form of cardiomyopathy that primarily affects the right ventricle and can cause arrhythmias. Unclassified cardiomyopathy includes those that do not fit into the other categories.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 568.","responses":[{"text":"Arrythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unclassified cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10258,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents with complaints of increasing breathlessness, fatigue, and weakness for the last 2 months. He has a history of mediastinal Hodgkin lymphoma treated with radiation therapy 5 years ago. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Restrictive cardiomyopathy** can occur as a late complication of **radiation therapy**, especially in patients with mediastinal malignancies like Hodgkin lymphoma. The radiation can lead to fibrosis of the myocardium, resulting in impaired ventricular filling and symptoms like breathlessness, fatigue, and weakness.\r\n\r\nDilated cardiomyopathy generally does not have a strong association with radiation therapy and is more commonly idiopathic or related to genetic mutations. Myocarditis secondary to viral infection usually has a more acute presentation, often with fever, and may not relate to the history of Hodgkin lymphoma and radiation therapy. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is generally a genetic disorder and does not relate well to the patient's medical history. Systolic heart failure is a broad term that describes a state rather than a specific type of heart disease; moreover, it does not specifically relate to the patient's history of radiation therapy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 574.","responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis secondary to viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systolic heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10261,"text":"Which one of these is a modifiable risk factor for the prevention of cardiovascular diseases?","explanation":"**Obesity** is a **modifiable risk factor** for cardiovascular diseases, meaning it can be changed through lifestyle modifications such as diet and exercise. Weight loss has been shown to improve lipid profiles, reduce blood pressure, and decrease the risk of developing diabetes, all of which contribute to a lower risk of cardiovascular disease.\r\n\r\nFamily history, age, genetics, and gender are all non-modifiable risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. These factors cannot be changed through lifestyle modifications or medical interventions. Therefore, they do not serve as targets for preventive strategies aimed at reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 494.","responses":[{"text":"Age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genetics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11867,"text":"Which of the following is not a characteristic of an ideal homicidal poison?","explanation":null,"reference":"Cardiology module; Forensic-medicine lecture slides; Topic: General toxicology-I; Subtopic: Properties of an ideal homicidal poison.","responses":[{"text":"Should resemble a natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orally ingested","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Easily available","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tasteless and odorless","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cheap in price","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11868,"text":"How many seconds does a normal PR interval last?","explanation":"The normal **PR interval** on an electrocardiogram (ECG) lasts between **0.12 to 0.20 seconds**, which is equivalent to 120 to 200 milliseconds. A prolonged PR interval may suggest a first-degree atrioventricular (AV) block or other forms of conduction abnormality.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 448.","responses":[{"text":"0.28 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.32 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.22 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.30 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.20 sec","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11870,"text":"What is the most common poison used to commit suicide in Pakistan?","explanation":"**Organophosphates** are often cited as a common poison used for **suicide** in Pakistan, particularly in rural areas where they are readily available as agricultural pesticides. These substances are highly toxic and act by inhibiting the activity of an enzyme called acetylcholinesterase, leading to accumulation of acetylcholine and causing severe symptoms that can be fatal if not treated promptly.\r\n\r\nAarsenic, barbiturates, kerosene oil, and potassium cyanide, are also toxic substances but are generally less accessible or less commonly used for this purpose in Pakistan.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh's Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 630.","responses":[{"text":"Kerosene oil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Organophosphates","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium cyanide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barbiturates","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11874,"text":"Which of the following works by blocking VLDL synthesis?","explanation":"**Nicotinic acid (niacin)** works by blocking VLDL (very low-density lipoprotein) synthesis. It inhibits the release of free fatty acids from adipose tissue, leading to **reduced hepatic VLDL synthesis**. This action subsequently lowers LDL levels.\r\n\r\nStatin drugs work primarily by inhibiting the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase, which plays a central role in the production of cholesterol in the liver. Fibrates mainly reduce triglycerides and can increase HDL levels but do not primarily block VLDL synthesis. Neomycin is an antibiotic and does not have a lipid-lowering effect. Resins, such as bile acid sequestrants, work by binding to bile acids in the intestine, leading to the excretion of cholesterol, but they also do not directly block VLDL synthesis.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 293.","responses":[{"text":"Resin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11881,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of nitrates?","explanation":"**Nitrates** such as nitroglycerin work by being converted to nitric oxide, which in turn activates **guanylate cyclase**. This leads to an increase in **cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP)** levels. Elevated cGMP levels cause smooth muscle relaxation, leading to vasodilation.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 111.","responses":[{"text":"Activate cGMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activate cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit cAMP and cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11885,"text":"A marble factory worker complains of cough and shortness of breath. He may have which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Silicosis** is an occupational lung disease commonly seen in workers exposed to **silica dust**, which is prevalent in **marble factories**. Symptoms typically include cough and shortness of breath.\r\n\r\nThe other anwer choices pertain to different types of occupational lung diseases related to distinct exposures: berylliosis is linked to beryllium, anthracosis to coal dust, pneumoconiosis is a broad term for dust-related lung diseases, and bagassosis is associated with sugarcane byproducts.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 688.","responses":[{"text":"Pneumoconiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berylliosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anthracosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bagassosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11887,"text":"An ethical review committee permission is necessary for most research studies. Which of the following research studies does not require permission?","explanation":"**Systematic reviews** involve the collation and analysis of **existing literature and data**, rather than direct interaction with human subjects or use of individual patient data that would necessitate ethical review. Therefore, they typically do not require ethical review committee permission.\r\n\r\nCohort prospective, cohort retrospective, case series, and cross-sectional studies all involve the collection and analysis of primary data, often from human subjects. These types of research usually require ethical review to ensure the safety, well-being, and privacy of the participants.","reference":"Suri H, Zawacki-Richter O, Kerres M, Bedenlier S, Bond M, Buntins K. Ethical considerations of conducting systematic reviews in educational research. Systematic Reviews in Educational Research: Methodology, Perspectives and Application. Published 2020. Accessed June 22, 2022. https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-658-27602-7_3","responses":[{"text":"Systemic review","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort - retrospective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort - prospective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional study","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11891,"text":"A 55-year-old male presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with abdominal discomfort and swelling of his legs for the past two years. On physical examination, jugular venous pressure is raised even when sitting up. The liver is enlarged and tender. Which of the following is most likely to cause these?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms, such as abdominal discomfort, leg swelling, raised jugular venous pressure, and enlarged, tender liver, are consistent with **right-sided heart failur**e. This condition leads to congestion of the systemic venous system, resulting in symptoms like **peripheral edema** and **hepatomegaly**. The **raised jugular venous pressure** is also a classic sign of right-sided heart failure.\r\n\r\nMyocarditis is an inflammation of the heart muscle that may lead to heart failure but is usually accompanied by other signs like fever and possibly a history of viral infection. Left-sided heart failure primarily manifests as pulmonary symptoms like dyspnea, rather than systemic congestion. Endocarditis involves inflammation of the heart valves and would be expected to show different symptoms, possibly including fever, heart murmurs, and other signs of infection. Myocardial infarction (heart attack) would typically present acutely with chest pain, and not the chronic symptoms described in this case.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 463.","responses":[{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right-sided heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-sided heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11892,"text":"What is the recommended amount of exercise to prevent cardiovascular disease?","explanation":"According to the American Heart Association and other healthcare organizations, it is generally recommended that individuals engage in at least 150 minutes of **moderate-intensity exercise** per week to **prevent cardiovascular disease**. This translates to **30 minutes a day, 5 days a week**.\r\n\r\nWhile more exercise is generally beneficial, the 30-minute, 5 days/week regimen is often cited as the baseline for cardiovascular health.","reference":"Tian D, Meng J. Exercise for prevention and relief of cardiovascular disease: prognoses, mechanisms, and approaches. Oxidative Medicine and Cellular Longevity. Published April 9, 2019. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6481017/","responses":[{"text":"10 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"15 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"60 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11894,"text":"Which of the following has a decreased risk of cardiovascular disease?","explanation":"**Polyunsaturated fats** are known to decrease the risk of cardiovascular disease. They can lower levels of low-density lipoprotein (LDL), or \"bad cholesterol,\" which reduces the risk of **atherosclerosis** and cardiovascular events.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnimal fat, cheese, saturated fats, and butter are generally high in saturated fats and cholesterol. Consumption of these fats has been associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, primarily due to their ability to elevate LDL cholesterol levels.","reference":"Ander BP, Dupasquier CM, Prociuk MA, Pierce GN. Polyunsaturated fatty acids and their effects on cardiovascular disease. Exp Clin Cardiol. 2003;8(4):164-172. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2719153/","responses":[{"text":"Cheese","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyunsaturated vegetable oil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Animal fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Butter","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12498,"text":"An industrialist asks a public health specialist about the measures he can take to control and prevent heart disease among employees. The public health specialist advises on the modifiable risk factors that can be addressed to lower the risk of cardiovascular diseases. Which one of the following options illustrates the modifiable risk factor that the industrialist can focus on?","explanation":"**Effective diabetes management** can significantly reduce cardiovascular risk as diabetes is a **modifiable risk factor**. Workplace programs can be implemented to educate employees about diabetes control, offer regular screening, and even provide lifestyle modification options like diet plans and exercise routines.\r\n\r\nEthnicity, family history, age, and gender are non-modifiable risk factors for heart disease and cannot be changed through interventions. Therefore, focusing on diabetes management would be a feasible and impactful approach.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Gender of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Age of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethnicity of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes management of employees","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12499,"text":"A 45-year-old man visits a doctor for his concern regarding his risk of heart disease. He explains that his father died of a heart attack at the age of 52 years. He seeks advice on diet. The doctor advises cutting down on the use of certain fats. Which of the following options illustrates the most important food group to be avoided by the person?","explanation":"**Saturated fats** are the most important food group to be avoided by the person concerned about his risk of heart disease. High intake of saturated fats is associated with **elevated levels of LDL cholesterol**, which is a risk factor for coronary artery disease.\r\n\r\nPolyunsaturated fats and monounsaturated fats are generally considered to be healthier fats and are not typically advised to be strictly avoided. Omega-6 fatty acids, while essential, can be pro-inflammatory in high amounts but are not usually the primary concern when it comes to reducing heart disease risk.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 493.\r\n\r\n(2) Briggs MA, Petersen KS, Kris-Etherton PM. Saturated fatty acids and cardiovascular disease: replacements for saturated fat to reduce cardiovascular risk. Healthcare. Published June 21, 2017. Accessed November 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5492032/","responses":[{"text":"Saturated fats","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega-6 fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyunsaturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monounsaturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12500,"text":"A public health specialist is contacted by the district health authorities for advice on primary preventive strategies for reducing the long-term risk of cardiovascular diseases in the population. Which one of the following options illustrates the most feasible solution for overall risk reduction in the population?","explanation":"**Building walking and cycling parks/tracks** is the most feasible solution for overall **risk reduction** in the population for **long-term cardiovascular diseases**. Physical activity is a key preventive measure for a variety of chronic diseases including cardiovascular diseases, obesity, and diabetes. Providing easily accessible facilities for exercise would likely encourage a more active lifestyle among the population.\r\n\r\nBanning alcohol, while it might have some positive effects on reducing alcohol-related cardiovascular issues, is not practical and would not be as effective. Screening for diabetes and heart disease is important but is a secondary preventive strategy rather than a primary one. Building polyclinics focuses more on treatment rather than primary prevention. Planting trees, although beneficial for mental well-being and air quality, would not directly influence cardiovascular health to the same extent as encouraging physical activity.","reference":"(1) Stewart J, Manmathan G, Wilkinson P. Primary prevention of cardiovascular disease: A review of contemporary guidance and literature. JRSM Cardiovascular Disease. Published January 1, 2017. Accessed November 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5331469/\r\n\r\n(2) Cardiology module; Community-medicine lecture slides; Topic: Role of diet and nutritional lifestyle modification; Sub-topic: Role of a healthy lifestyle in prevention.","responses":[{"text":"Planting trees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Building walking and cycling parks/ tracks","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Screening for diabetes and heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Building polyclinics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Banning alcohol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12502,"text":"A 45-year-old woman on antiarrhythmic therapy comes with signs and symptoms of hypothyroidism (such as weight gain, constipation, cold intolerance, and menstrual irregularities).\r\nHypothyroidism is a possible consequence of prolonged therapy with which of the following drugs?","explanation":"**Amiodarone** is an antiarrhythmic medication that has iodine-containing compounds, and its use can lead to **thyroid dysfunction**, including **hypothyroidism**.\r\n\r\nProcainamide, quinidine, mexiletine, and sotalol are also antiarrhythmic agents but they are generally not associated with thyroid dysfunction.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 647-648.","responses":[{"text":"Sotalol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amiodarone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mexiletine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12505,"text":"A patient receiving a class I antiarrhythmic agent on a long-term basis complains of fatigue, low-grade fever, and joint pain suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). The patient is most likely using which of the following antiarrhythmic drugs?","explanation":"The patient is most likely using **procainamide**, a class IA antiarrhythmic agent. Procainamide is known to cause **drug-induced lupus erythematosus**, which can present with symptoms such as fatigue, low-grade fever, and joint pain, mimicking systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).\r\n\r\nQuinidine is also a class IA antiarrhythmic but is not commonly associated with drug-induced lupus. Propranolol is a beta-blocker, not a class I antiarrhythmic. Lidocaine is a class IB antiarrhythmic primarily used for ventricular arrhythmias and is not associated with drug-induced lupus. Flecainide is class IC antiarrhythmic used for supraventricular arrhythmias and ventricular tachycardia but is also not known to induce lupus-like symptoms.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 238.","responses":[{"text":"Flecainide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12506,"text":"A 36-year-old male smoker, a known case of heart failure, presents to the emergency with severe lower limb edema with difficulty breathing. Which of the following is the drug of choice in this case (that can improve breathing capacity by resolving edema)?","explanation":"**Chlorothiazide** is the drug of choice to improve breathing capacity by resolving **edema**. Chlorothiazide is a thiazide diuretic that helps to **remove excess fluid** from the body, which in turn can relieve symptoms like edema and difficulty breathing.\r\n\r\nPropranolol is a beta-blocker, mainly used for hypertension and arrhythmias but not primarily for resolving edema. Captopril is an ACE inhibitor and is mainly used for hypertension and heart failure but is not specifically focused on resolving acute edema. Prazosin is an alpha-blocker used for hypertension, and sodium nitroprusside is a potent vasodilator used in hypertensive emergencies; neither are ideal for treating edema.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 215.","responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorothiazide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium nitroprusside","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12507,"text":"A 45-year-old patient presents to the emergency in an unconscious state. Blood analysis is done and the result shows that the patient has hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia, while the electrocardiogram suggests heart failure. Which of the following drugs is contraindicated in this case?","explanation":"In a patient with hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia, the use of **digoxin** is contraindicated. Hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia can increase the risk of **digitalis toxicity**, which could further exacerbate heart failure and potentially lead to fatal arrhythmias.\r\n\r\nSpironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic and could actually be beneficial in treating hypokalemia. Ramipril is an ACE inhibitor commonly used in heart failure. Isosorbide dinitrate is a vasodilator used for symptomatic relief in heart failure. Milrinone is a phosphodiesterase inhibitor used in acute heart failure to improve symptoms.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 244.","responses":[{"text":"Ramipril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isosorbite dinitrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Milrinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12519,"text":"A 65-year-old woman with a medical history of type II diabetes, obesity, and hypertension visits the outpatient department. She had been told her cholesterol was elevated in the past and states that she has been following a \"low cholesterol diet\" for the past 6 months after seeing a dietician. A fasting lipid profile is performed and revealed an LDL (low-density lipoprotein) of 160 mg/dl (normal value should be less than 100 mg/dl), HDL (high-density lipoprotein) of 45 mg/dl (should be 250 mg/dl), and total cholesterol of 250mg/dl (normal range between 125-200mg/dl). Which of the following drugs should be preferred for the patient?","explanation":"Given the patient's **elevated LDL cholesterol level** and her history of type II diabetes, obesity, and hypertension, **simvastatin** or another statin would be the most appropriate choice. Statins are the **first-line therapy** for lowering LDL cholesterol and are particularly beneficial for patients with multiple cardiovascular risk factors, such as this patient. \r\n\r\nFinofibrates and gemfibrozil are more effective in treating elevated triglycerides rather than LDL cholesterol. Propranolol is a beta-blocker and is not used for lowering lipid levels. Niacin also has lipid-lowering effects but is usually reserved for cases not controlled by other medications due to its side effect profile.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 290.\r\n\r\n(2)  Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 328.","responses":[{"text":"Gemfibrozil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propanolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Finofibrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simvastatin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12520,"text":"A 55-year-old Caucasian man presents with polyuria, and polydipsia for the past 2 months. He has a 3-year history of poorly controlled hypertriglyceridemia. His initial fasting serum cholesterol is 250 mg/dl, triglycerides are 928 mg/dl (normal value 200 mg/dl), and high-density lipoprotein (HDL) is 30 mg/dl (should be 250 mg/dl). Which of the following is the best treatment option for this patient?","explanation":"The best treatment option for this patient with **severely elevated triglycerides** and a history of hypertriglyceridemia is **gemfibrozil**. This medication is a fibrate, specifically used for lowering triglyceride levels. Elevated triglycerides can lead to symptoms like the ones described (polyuria, polydipsia) and increase the risk of pancreatitis. \r\n\r\nAtorvastatin is primarily used for lowering LDL cholesterol rather than triglycerides. Colesevelam and ezetimibe are also more focused on reducing LDL cholesterol. Propranolol is a beta-blocker and is not primarily used to treat dyslipidemia.","reference":"(1) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 328.\r\n\r\n(2) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 293-294.","responses":[{"text":"Colesevelam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propanolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gemfibrozil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atorvastatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ezetimibe","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12522,"text":"A 55-year-old female patient is admitted to the hospital with a progressive increase in breathlessness, orthopnea, and ankle edema over the previous 3 weeks. She is apyrexial yet tachypnoeic (25/min) with a low-volume pulse. Echocardiography shows a dilated heart (left ventricular end-diastolic distension (LVEDD) 650 mm) with anterior and septal hypokinesis. She is diagnosed with a case of progressive systolic heart failure and the physician decides to start digitalis on this patient. What is the mechanism of action of digitalis by which it can increase the contractility of cardiac muscle?","explanation":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, digitalis **increases the intracellular Na+ ion concentration**. This leads to a reduced activity of the Na+/Ca2+ exchanger, resulting in increased intracellular calcium concentration, which in turn enhances myocardial contractility. \r\n\r\nThis mechanism is particularly important in conditions like **systolic heart failure**, where the contractile function of the heart is compromised.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 242.","responses":[{"text":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, decreasing the intracellular Ca+ ion concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, decreasing the intracellular Na+ ion concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, increasing the intracellular Cl- ion concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, increasing the intracellular Na+ ion concentration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By inhibiting the Na+/K+ ATPase, increasing the intracellular K+ ion concentration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12524,"text":"An elderly patient with a history of heart disease is brought to the emergency room with difficulty breathing. Examination reveals that she has pulmonary edema. Which treatment is indicated using the most potent diuretic?","explanation":"**Furosemide** is the most potent diuretic among the options and is the treatment of choice for **acute pulmonary edema**. \r\n\r\nAcetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor and not potent enough for treating acute conditions. Spironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic, which is also weaker and not suitable for immediate management of acute pulmonary edema. Chlorthalidone and hydrochlorothiazide are thiazide diuretics, which are less potent than loop diuretics like furosemide and not ideal for rapid symptom relief in cases of acute pulmonary edema.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 222.","responses":[{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochlorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12525,"text":"A 45-year-old male complains of constipation. He is recently started on two antihypertensives due to elevated systolic blood pressure (greater than 20 mmHg above goal). His current medications include lisinopril, chlorthalidone, verapamil, rosuvastatin, and aspirin. Which is most likely contributing to his constipation?","explanation":"**Verapamil** is most likely contributing to the patient's **constipation**. Verapamil is a calcium channel blocker used for treating hypertension and other cardiovascular conditions.\r\n\r\nAspirin generally does not cause constipation; instead, it can irritate the stomach lining.\r\n\r\nChlorthalidone is a diuretic that typically causes more urination rather than constipation.\r\n\r\nLisinopril is an ACE inhibitor used for hypertension and may cause cough but not constipation.\r\n\r\nValsartan is an angiotensin II receptor blocker (ARB) and is not currently on the patient's medication list, but it also typically does not cause constipation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 212-213.","responses":[{"text":"Valsartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lisinopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Verapamil","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12526,"text":"A 52-year-old female has uncontrolled hypertension (blood pressure 154/82 mm Hg) and is on treatment with lisinopril. She recently had a myocardial infarction and her past medical history includes diabetes and hyperlipidemia. Considering her indications, which agent may be appropriate to add to her antihypertensive therapy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 207-208.","responses":[{"text":"Clonidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Olmesartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoprolol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12527,"text":"A 55-year-old man experiences crushing substernal chest pain after arriving at work one morning. Over the next 5 hours, the pain persists and begins to radiate to his left arm. He becomes diaphoretic and short of breath but waits until the end of his 8-hour shift to go to the hospital. Which of the following laboratory tests has elevated value and would be most useful for the diagnosis of this patient on admission to the hospital?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms strongly suggest an **acute myocardial infarction (heart attack)**. The most useful laboratory test for diagnosis on admission in this case would be **CK-MB fraction (creatine kinase-MB)**. This is a cardiac-specific isoenzyme that starts to rise within 4-6 hours after the onset of myocardial infarction and peaks at about 18-24 hours.\r\n\r\n\r\nC-reactive protein is a marker of inflammation and is not specific for myocardial infarction.\r\n\r\nALT (alanine aminotransferase) and AST (aspartate aminotransferase) are liver enzymes and would not be elevated specifically due to a myocardial infarction.\r\n\r\nLDH-1 (lactate dehydrogenase) can be elevated in myocardial infarction, but it is not as specific as CK-MB and takes longer to rise.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 547.\r\n\r\n(2) Patibandla S, Gupta K, Alsayouri K. Cardiac Enzymes. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545216/","responses":[{"text":"ALT (alanine aminotransferase)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C-reactive protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LDH-1 (lactate dehydrogenase)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AST (aspartate aminotransferase)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CK-MB fraction (creatine kinase-MB)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12528,"text":"A 52-year-old man has a sudden onset of severe substernal chest pain that radiates to the neck. On physical examination, he is afebrile but has tachycardia, hyperventilation, and hypotension. No cardiac murmurs are heard on auscultation. Emergent coronary angiography shows a thrombotic occlusion of the left circumflex artery and areas of 50% to 70% narrowing in the proximal circumflex and anterior descending arteries. Which of the following complications of this disease is most likely to occur within 1 hour of these events?","explanation":"**Ventricular fibrillation** is the most likely complication to occur within 1 hour of these events. The patient has signs of **acute myocardial infarction (MI)**, characterized by severe substernal chest pain, tachycardia, hyperventilation, and hypotension. Ventricular fibrillation is a **life-threatening arrhythmia** that can occur early in the course of an acute MI and requires **immediate treatment** to prevent sudden cardiac death.\r\n\r\nThromboembolism is generally a later complication and not as immediate as ventricular fibrillation. Valvular insufficiency is unlikely to develop within an hour of an acute MI. Myocardial rupture typically occurs days to weeks following a myocardial infarction, not within 1 hour. Pericarditis is also a complication that tends to occur days to weeks after an acute MI.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 74.","responses":[{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valvular insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboembolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial rupture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular fibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12529,"text":"An infant born at term is noted to have cyanosis during the first week of life. On examination, a heart murmur is auscultated. Investigations show an overriding aorta, ventricular septal defect, right ventricular thickening, and pulmonic stenosis. This infant is most likely to have an inherited mutation involving which of the following genes?","explanation":"**NOTCH signaling** is involved in **cardiac development**, and mutations in NOTCH2 have been implicated in the development of congenital heart diseases, including **tetralogy of Fallot**.\r\n\r\n\r\nBeta-myosin heavy chain (Beta-MHC) mutations are associated with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, not tetralogy of Fallot.\r\n\r\nFibrillin-1 mutations are related to Marfan syndrome, which may cause a variety of cardiovascular issues but not tetralogy of Fallot.\r\n\r\nKCNQ1 is associated with Long QT syndrome, a different cardiac disorder involving the electrical system of the heart.\r\n\r\nTransthyretin mutations are associated with familial amyloid cardiomyopathy, not congenital heart defects like tetralogy of Fallot.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 535.","responses":[{"text":"NOTCH2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrillin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-myosin heavy chain (Beta-MHC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"KCNQI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transthyretin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12530,"text":"A 2-year-old child is brought to the physician for a routine examination. Physical examination shows a low-pitched cardiac murmur. An echocardiogram shows the presence of ostium secundum, with a 1-cm defect. Which of the following abnormalities is most likely to be found in this child?","explanation":"**Ostium secundum** defect is a type of **atrial septal defect**. Atrial septal defects often result in a **left-to-right shunt** because the left atrial pressure is usually higher than right atrial pressure. This shunting can lead to increased flow through the pulmonary circulation but is typically well-tolerated in children and may not present with symptoms. Over time, if untreated, this can lead to pulmonary hypertension, but it is not an immediate concern in a 2-year-old.\r\n\r\n- Cyanosis is more commonly seen in conditions with a right-to-left shunt, like Tetralogy of Fallot, and not in atrial septal defects.\r\n- Pulmonary hypertension might develop in long-standing, untreated cases but is unlikely in a 2-year-old.\r\n- Mural thrombosis is also unlikely in a 2-year-old child with an ostium secundum defect.\r\n- Pericardial effusion is not a typical finding associated with atrial septal defects.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 534.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-to-right shunt","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mural thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12531,"text":"A 58-year-old man has had progressive dyspnea for 1 year. On physical examination, extensive rales are heard on chest auscultation. An echocardiogram shows that the left ventricular wall is markedly hypertrophied. A chest radiograph shows pulmonary edema and a prominent left-sided heart shadow. Which of the following conditions has most likely produced these findings?","explanation":"The progressive dyspnea, extensive rales on chest auscultation, pulmonary edema on chest radiograph, and a markedly hypertrophied left ventricular wall on echocardiogram are all indicators of **left-sided heart failure**. **Systemic hypertension** is a common cause of left ventricular hypertrophy and resultant heart failure.\r\n\r\n- Tricuspid valve regurgitation primarily affects the right side of the heart and would not result in left ventricular hypertrophy.\r\n- Silicosis primarily affects the lungs and would not directly lead to left ventricular hypertrophy or the other heart-related symptoms described.\r\n- Centrilobular emphysema is a lung condition that can lead to right-sided heart failure but would not cause left ventricular hypertrophy.\r\n- Chronic alcoholism can lead to dilated cardiomyopathy but is less likely to cause the left ventricular hypertrophy seen in the echocardiogram.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Centrilobular emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid valve regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic alcoholism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12577,"text":"A 15-year-old boy is admitted to the hospital with shortness of breath and chest pain. He has painful knees and elbows. Examination shows a few nodules below the skin. He has a history of a sore throat from a few weeks back. Which of the following could be the bacteria responsible for his sore throat?","explanation":"This patient has symptoms suggestive of **acute rheumatic fever**, which is most commonly caused by ***Streptococcus pyogenes***. This bacterium is commonly implicated in **pharyngitis** and is known to be the triggering infection for rheumatic fever, which can present with **joint pain, nodules under the skin**, and symptoms related to heart disease.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 557-559.","responses":[{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus agalactiae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pyogenes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12578,"text":"The biopsy of the heart of a 35-year-old patient, who died because of a sudden cardiac event, shows fibrosis with thickened and retracted mitral valve cusps. Which of the following would she have been suffering from?","explanation":"The findings of **fibrosis with thickened** and **retracted mitral valve cusps** in the heart biopsy suggest that the patient was most likely suffering from **chronic rheumatic heart disease**. This condition is a sequela of acute rheumatic fever and is characterized by fibrotic and calcified valves, commonly involving the mitral valve. It can lead to valve stenosis or insufficiency and is a major risk factor for sudden cardiac events.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 558.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic rheumatic heart disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right-sided cardiac failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12580,"text":"A 12-year-old boy is admitted to the hospital with jerking movements of limbs and shortness of breath. He has complaints of painful joints. Examination shows an erythematous rash on the skin. To make a diagnosis of rheumatic fever, you need to utilize Jones criteria. Minor Jones criteria include which of the following?","explanation":"In the Jones criteria for diagnosing rheumatic fever, **fever** is considered a **minor criterion**. Other minor criteria include **arthralgia (joint pain without swelling), elevated acute-phase reactants like ESR (erythrocyte sedimentation rate) and CRP (C-reactive protein)**, and a **prolonged PR interval** on EKG. \r\n\r\nCarditis, subcutaneous nodules, erythema marginatum, and migratory polyarthritis of large joints are considered major criteria.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Migratory polyarthritis of large joints","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcutaneous nodules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythema marginatum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12582,"text":"A 5-year-old child presents with shortness of breath and chest pain. He complains of coughing during the night. On auscultation, the physician detects a soft, high-pitched, early diastolic murmur. An echocardiogram shows aortic regurgitation. What is the most common predisposing condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 554.\r\n\r\n(2) Dewaswala N, Chait R. Aortic regurgitation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 28, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555944/","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicuspid aortic valve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12584,"text":"A patient is admitted to the cardiology ward with complaints of shortness of breath upon exertion, cough during the night, fatigue, and swelling of legs and feet. A systolic murmur is audible. He is diagnosed with mitral insufficiency. What is the most likely cause of mitral valve prolapse?","explanation":"The most likely cause of **mitral valve prolapse** in this patient is **Marfan syndrome**. This connective tissue disorder often leads to **weakening of the mitral valve leaflets**, causing them to prolapse into the left atrium during systole, thereby leading to mitral insufficiency. \r\n\r\nPericardial effusion primarily affects the pericardium and not the mitral valve. Calcification and post-inflammatory scarring are less commonly associated with prolapse; they are more often causes of stenosis or regurgitation without the prolapse. Hypertension generally affects the aortic valve more than the mitral valve.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 520.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-inflammatory scarring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcification","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12585,"text":"A 66-year-old patient develops chest pain with a rapid heartbeat. He is also feeling shortness of breath and is slightly dizzy. He is diagnosed with aortic stenosis. What is the most common cause of aortic stenosis?","explanation":"The most common cause of **aortic stenosis** in elderly patients is **degenerative calcific stenosis**. Over time, the aortic valve can become calcified and stiff, reducing its ability to fully open and close. This can lead to a **narrowing of the aortic valve opening**, known as aortic stenosis.\r\n\r\n- Though hypertension can contribute to heart disease, it is not the most common cause of aortic stenosis.\r\n  \r\n- Conduction defects in the heart usually affect the electrical system of the heart but are not a cause of aortic stenosis.\r\n\r\n- Obstructive cardiomyopathy is a different form of heart disease and is not the most common cause of aortic stenosis.\r\n\r\n- Pericarditis refers to inflammation of the pericardium, the outer lining of the heart, and is not related to aortic stenosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 554.","responses":[{"text":"Conduction defects in the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Degenerative calcific stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12586,"text":"Embryologically, where do the left pulmonary artery and the ductus arteriosus arise from?","explanation":"The left pulmonary artery arises from the **left sixth aortic arch**, while the **ductus arteriosus** arises from the same left sixth aortic arch. \r\n\r\n- The left fourth aortic arch gives rise to the aortic arch on the left side and the right subclavian artery on the right side.\r\n\r\n- The left fifth aortic arch typically involutes and does not give rise to these structures.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 320.","responses":[{"text":"Left sixth aortic arch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left sixth and fourth aortic arches, respectively","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left fourth aortic arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left fourth and sixth aortic arches, respectively","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left fifth aortic arch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12587,"text":"After 6 hours of delivery, a baby crashes in the neonatal intensive care unit (NICU). What infusion will you start to save the life of the baby?","explanation":"**Epinephrine infusion** is often used in **neonatal resuscitation** to address severe bradycardia or cardiac arrest. This potent vasoactive agent increases both heart rate and myocardial contractility, aiming to rapidly improve hemodynamics.\r\n\r\nDopamine is a vasoactive medication often used to improve blood pressure and cardiac output. However, it is generally not the first-line choice for neonatal resuscitation during severe bradycardia or cardiac arrest.\r\n\r\nDobutamine is another vasoactive medication used to increase cardiac output and treat heart failure. Again, it is not typically used as the first-line treatment for life-threatening emergencies in neonates.\r\n\r\nProstaglandins like PGE1 are often used to keep a patent ductus arteriosus open in certain congenital heart defects. They are not used for emergency resuscitation.\r\n\r\nMilrinone is a phosphodiesterase inhibitor used in heart failure to increase myocardial contractility and decrease pulmonary vascular resistance. It is not commonly used in emergency resuscitation of neonates.","reference":"Vali P, Sankaran D, Rawat M, Berkelhamer S, Lakshminrusimha S. Epinephrine in neonatal resuscitation. Children. Published April 2, 2019. Accessed November 28, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6518253/","responses":[{"text":"Dopamine infusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandin infusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Milrinone infusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine infusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dobutamine infusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12588,"text":"In a 20-year-old patient, during the cardiovascular examination, you hear a pansystolic murmur of grade 4/6 Intensity at the left sternal border. What is your most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"A **pansystolic (or holosystolic)** murmur at the left sternal border is most commonly associated with **ventricular septal defect (VSD)**. This murmur occurs throughout systole, without a silent interval.\r\n\r\nAortic regurgitation typically presents with an early diastolic decrescendo murmur at the left sternal border or aortic area, not a pansystolic murmur.\r\n\r\nPulmonary regurgitation would present with a diastolic murmur, not a pansystolic one.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect is generally associated with a wide, fixed splitting of the second heart sound and may have a systolic ejection murmur, but not a pansystolic murmur.\r\n\r\nMitral stenosis would produce a diastolic murmur at the apex, not a pansystolic murmur at the left sternal border.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12590,"text":"A 25-year-old man presents for a medical checkup before job recruitment. On examination, a wide fixed splitting of the second heart sound and a systolic flow murmur is found over the pulmonary area. The patient denies any symptoms. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"A **wide, fixed splitting** of the second heart sound is classically associated with **atrial septal defect (ASD)**. The **systolic flow murmur** over the pulmonary area is a result of increased flow across the pulmonary valve due to the left-to-right shunt of blood from the atrial septal defect.\r\n\r\nPatent ductus arteriosus typically manifests with a continuous \"machinery\" murmur, not a wide, fixed splitting of S2. \r\n\r\nMitral stenosis usually results in a diastolic murmur at the apex with no fixed splitting of S2. \r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect would generally produce a holosystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border. \r\n\r\nAortic stenosis typically manifests as a systolic ejection murmur at the right upper sternal border.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 459.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12591,"text":"A 17-day-old infant is brought to the pediatrician's clinic for poor feeding. She is born to a first-time mother without any complications. Cardiac examination reveals a grade 3/6 continuous machine-like murmur over the left infraclavicular area with a widened pulse pressure. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"A **continuous \"machinery\" murmur** is characteristic of **patent ductus areriosus (PDA)**. Additionally, **widened pulse pressure** is often seen in cases of PDA. This congenital condition often presents within the first few weeks of life with symptoms like **poor feeding**.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect usually presents with a systolic ejection murmur, not a continuous murmur.\r\n\r\nAortic stenosis would typically manifest as a systolic ejection murmur heard at the right upper sternal border.\r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect is typically associated with a holosystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border.\r\n\r\nAortic regurgitation usually manifests later in life and also doesn't present with a continuous murmur.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 461.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12592,"text":"A 67-year-old man presents to the emergency department with typical chest pain. Medical history includes diabetes and hypertension. His troponin levels are raised. Coronary angiography demonstrates diffuse three-vessel coronary artery disease and he has a poor left ventricular function with low ejection fraction. Which of the following is not the risk factor for the development of ischemic heart disease?","explanation":"While **anxiety and stress** can contribute to cardiovascular strain, they are not classified as traditional risk factors for ischemic heart disease like hypertension, male gender, diabetes, and smoking. These latter factors have a well-established link with the pathogenesis of ischemic heart disease and are directly implicated in the progression of the disease.\r\n\r\nThey have been shown in numerous studies to contribute to the development and progression of coronary artery atherosclerosis, which can lead to ischemic events.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Male gender","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anxiety and stress","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12670,"text":"A 55-year-old male patient with diabetes with a family history of ischemic heart disease comes to the outpatient department with his echocardiography report showing a low ejection fraction. The doctor advises him to get his angiography done, which reveals diffuse three-vessel disease. What is the treatment of choice for diffuse three-vessel coronary artery disease along with low ejection fraction?","explanation":"**Coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG)** is generally the preferred treatment for patients with significant **three-vessel disease**, particularly when there is a **low ejection fraction**, which indicates compromised heart function. CABG has been shown to improve survival in these cases as compared to other treatment modalities.\r\n\r\nMedical treatment alone is not sufficient for diffuse three-vessel disease, especially with a low ejection fraction. Yoga and meditation, while beneficial for stress reduction and overall well-being, are not adequate for treating severe coronary artery disease. Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) might not be suitable for diffuse three-vessel disease. Herbal treatments are not a validated approach for treating severe coronary artery disease.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 491-492.","responses":[{"text":"Yoga and meditation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Herbal treatment along with honey and apple juice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary artery bypass surgery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical treatment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12671,"text":"A 55-years-male patient comes to the emergency room with severe chest pain. His electrocardiogram shows inferior wall ST-elevation myocardial infarction. While the doctor is managing the patient, he develops bradycardia and syncopal attacks. The cardiac monitor shows complete atrioventricular dissociation. What is the next best step of the treatment?","explanation":"In the setting of an inferior wall ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) with **complete atrioventricular (AV) dissociation** that is symptomatic (bradycardia and syncopal attacks), **immediate temporary transvenous pacing** is indicated to maintain heart rate and perfusion.\r\n\r\nChest compressions and intravascular adrenaline are generally reserved for cardiac arrest situations. Ventolin nebulization has no role in managing AV block. Intravenous dopamine infusion could be a temporizing measure but is not the definitive treatment for complete AV block, especially in the setting of a myocardial infarction where rapid, definitive intervention is crucial.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Inject intravascular adrenaline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nebulize with ventolin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start transvenous intracardiac temporary pacing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediately start the chest compressions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start intravenous dopamine infusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12672,"text":"A 75-year-old lady comes with a complaint of missed beats. She has history of stable angina for the last 10 years. She is taking atenolol 100 mg once a day and ivabradine 5 mg twice a day along with nitrates. Her blood pressure is 110/50 mmHg and her pulse is 66/minute but regularly irregular. On further inquiry, she admits that she sometimes feels dizzy. Your senior colleague informs you that she is having a Wenkebach phenomenon. Which one will be the best management step?","explanation":"**Wenkebach phenomenon, or Mobitz type I**, is a second-degree atrioventricular (AV) block that is generally benign and often does not require pacing. The patient is already on medications that lower heart rate (atenolol and ivabradine), and this could be contributing to her condition and symptoms. **Reducing or stopping these medications** while closely observing the cardiac rhythm would be appropriate.\r\n\r\nNebulizing with ventolin is not indicated for AV block. Intravenous atropine is typically reserved for symptomatic bradycardia that is immediately life-threatening, which does not seem to be the case here. Permanent pacing and transvenous temporary pacing are generally not first-line treatments for Wenkebach unless the patient is highly symptomatic and other treatments have failed.","reference":"(1) Mangi MA, Jones WM, Mansour MK, Napier L. Atrioventricular block second-degree. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482359/\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 477-478.","responses":[{"text":"Inject intravenous atropine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transvenous temporary pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Permanent pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nebulize with ventolin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Readjust the medical treatment and observe the cardiac rhythm","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12675,"text":"A 58-year-old male patient comes to the clinic with chest pain and profuse sweating for the last hour. He has a 20-pack year history of smoking. Medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg and his pulse is 100/min. His electrocardiogram shows extensive anterior wall myocardial Infarction. He is given aspirin 300 mg and clopidogrel 300 mg along with sublingual nitrate. As soon as he swallows the tablets, he develops fits-like activity and his blood pressure rapidly drops. The cardiac monitor shows bizarre and chaotic electrical activity. Which one is the next best step of treatment?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with \"bizarre and chaotic electrical activity\" on the cardiac monitor likely indicates **ventricular fibrillation**, a life-threatening arrhythmia that is a medical emergency requiring **immediate electrical defibrillation**. Defibrillation is the most effective treatment to restore normal heart rhythm and should not be delayed.\r\n\r\nIntravenous dopamine infusion, intubation, intravenous diazepam, and intravenous lignocaine are not the first-line treatments for ventricular fibrillation.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 456-457.","responses":[{"text":"Inject intravenous lignocaine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Start intravenous dopamine infusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediate electrical defibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inject intravenous diazepam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intubate the patient","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12676,"text":"A 25-year-old male patient comes to the clinic with chest pain and a dizzy feeling. On examination, he has an ejection systolic murmur over the base of the heart. His echocardiography report shows severe aortic stenosis. What is the most common cause of aortic stenosis worldwide?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 521.\r\n\r\n(2) Pujari SH, Agasthi P. Aortic stenosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed November 28, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557628/","responses":[{"text":"Sub-aortic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital atriovetricular stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Senile degeneration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicuspid aortic valve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12725,"text":"What is the standard test for aortic stenosis?","explanation":"**Echocardiography** is the **gold standard** for diagnosing **aortic stenosis**. It allows for direct visualization of the aortic valve and provides detailed information about valve anatomy, function, and the **degree of stenosis**. It also provides data on left ventricular function and other cardiac structures, which is crucial for clinical management.\r\n\r\nCardiac catheterization is more invasive and usually reserved for cases where echocardiographic findings are inconclusive or for preoperative evaluation. \r\n\r\nCardiac MRI provides detailed images but is not the first-line diagnostic tool for aortic stenosis. \r\n\r\nChest x-ray and electrocardiography (ECG) may show signs suggestive of aortic stenosis but are not diagnostic tests for the condition.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 522.","responses":[{"text":"Chest X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac MRI (magnetic resonance imaging)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac catheterization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12726,"text":"Which of the following is an indication for secondary prophylaxis in patients with rheumatic heart disease if the patient is allergic to penicillin?","explanation":"**Sulfadiazine** is an alternative to penicillin for prophylaxis in patients who are**allergic to penicillin**. It is effective in preventing recurrent attacks of rheumatic fever, which can further damage the heart valves.\r\n\r\nAmoxicillin is a penicillin derivative and would not be suitable for someone with a penicillin allergy. Rifampin is generally reserved for very specific cases, like tuberculosis, and is not recommended for rheumatic heart disease prophylaxis. Carbapenem and meropenem are broad-spectrum antibiotics that are not typically used for this purpose and would also not be suitable for someone with a penicillin allergy.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 517.","responses":[{"text":"Carbapenem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meropenem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfadiazine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12727,"text":"A 28-year-old male smoker is feeling atypical chest pain for two weeks. He is anxious as his cousin died at the age of 40 and he was also a smoker. Which one is the best test for screening for ischemic heart disease?","explanation":"This 28-year-old male smoker, given his family history and symptoms, would be at low-to-intermediate risk for heart disease.\r\n\r\nThe **exercise treadmill stress test** is a commonly used initial test for young adults who are symptomatic but at low-to-intermediate risk. It provides information on exercise tolerance and helps to identify any abnormal heart rhythms or signs of ischemic heart disease under stress conditions.\r\n\r\nCardiac MRI and coronary angiography are highly specific but are generally reserved for those who have other positive initial screening tests, or who are at high risk. Echocardiography is typically used to assess structural and functional aspects of the heart but is not the best initial screening test for ischemic heart disease. The head-up tilt table test is used for the evaluation of syncope or fainting and is not relevant for ischemic heart disease.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 488.","responses":[{"text":"Coronary angiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Head up tilt table test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise treadmill stress test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12729,"text":"A 32-year-old male comes to you with his lipid profile report that is showing dyslipidemia. He is a pilot by profession and is anxious about his job and fitness. He tells that he has a family history of dyslipidemia and one of his uncles died of a heart attack at the age of 40. He is otherwise healthy and denies any symptoms of angina. Considering his high-risk profession, which one is the best test to screen him for ischemic heart disease?","explanation":"**Coronary angiography** is considered the gold standard for diagnosing **coronary artery disease**. It provides direct visualization of the coronary arteries and can identify areas of **stenosis or blockage**. In a high-risk individual such as a pilot, early and accurate detection is crucial.\r\n\r\nEchocardiography primarily evaluates cardiac structure and function but is not as sensitive or specific for ischemic heart disease. Myocardial perfusion scans are generally used in people who already have symptoms or positive results on other tests. Cardiac MRI is a useful diagnostic tool but is generally not used for initial screening. Cardiac CT could provide useful data, but coronary angiography remains the gold standard for detecting significant coronary artery disease.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiac computed tomography (CT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial perfusion scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12730,"text":"What is the mechanism of action for cyanide poisoning?","explanation":"**Cytochrome oxidase** is a crucial enzyme in the mitochondrial electron transport chain responsible for cellular respiration. By inhibiting this enzyme, cyanide impairs **cellular respiration**, leading to cellular hypoxia and death.\r\n\r\nCyanide does not act by reducing hematin, inhibiting mitochondria as a whole, or inhibiting mitochondrial enzymes not specific to the electron transport chain. It also does not inhibit protoplasm.","reference":"(1) Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 582.\r\n\r\n(2) Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 538.","responses":[{"text":"Reduction of hematin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of mitochondria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of mitochondrial enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of protoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of cytochrome oxidase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12731,"text":"A person ingested bleach containing oxalic acid. What is the immediate at-home antidote that can be administered?","explanation":"Chalk can be administered as an **immediate at-home antidote** for **oxalic acid ingestion**.\r\n\r\n**Chalk** contains calcium carbonate, which can bind to oxalic acid to form calcium oxalate, reducing the systemic absorption of oxalic acid and thus mitigating the risk of hypocalcemia.\r\n\r\nActivated charcoal is generally not effective for corrosive substances like oxalic acid. Limewater may be too alkaline and may not be readily available at home for immediate use. Chocolate, while containing some amount of calcium, is not an appropriate antidote for oxalic acid poisoning.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Limewater","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Charcoal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chocolate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated charcoal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chalk","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12732,"text":"Which of the following corrosive causes hypocalcemia?","explanation":"**Oxalic acid** can bind to calcium to form calcium oxalate, which is insoluble. This can lead to a decrease in serum calcium levels, resulting in **hypocalcemia**.\r\n\r\nAcetic acid, phenol, sulfuric acid, and MgSO4 do not typically cause hypocalcemia. These substances have other toxic effects but do not specifically bind calcium in a way that leads to hypocalcemia.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 485.","responses":[{"text":"Sulphuric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MgSO4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12733,"text":"What is the main difference between cyanide and hydrocyanic acid?","explanation":"The main difference is that **cyanide** is a **salt**, while **hydrocyanic acid** is its acidic form.\r\n\r\nCyanide generally refers to various salt forms like sodium cyanide (NaCN) or potassium cyanide (KCN). **Hydrocyanic acid** is the acidic form (HCN) of cyanide. In this form, it is a **weak, volatile acid**.\r\n\r\nNeither hydrocyanic acid nor cyanide is particularly corrosive in the way that other acids and bases can be.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 538.","responses":[{"text":"None of the above","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocyanic acid is a salt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanide is a salt","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocyanic acid has corrosive properties","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanide has corrosive properties","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12735,"text":"What is the main antidote for cyanide poisoning?","explanation":"**Methylene blue** is used as an antidote for **cyanide poisoning** as it helps to convert the toxic methemoglobin back into hemoglobin. It serves to provide an alternate pathway for cyanide to bind, thus freeing up the cytochrome oxidase system and allowing cellular respiration to return to normal.\r\n\r\nCharcoal is used for absorbing ingested poisons but is ineffective against cyanide. Chalk has no role in treating cyanide poisoning. Tannic acid is not used as an antidote for cyanide. Nitroprusside is actually a medication that can cause cyanide toxicity and is not an antidote for it.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 539.","responses":[{"text":"Charcoal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tannic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroprusside","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chalk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylene blue","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12736,"text":"A 10-year-old boy is brought to the outpatient department with a complaint of fever for the past 10 days. The fever is high grade. He also has complaints of pain in his right shoulder and right knee pain. For the past 2 days, he is complaining of a respiratory tract infection from 3 weeks back. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Rheumatic fever** commonly occurs in children and often follows a **streptococcal infection (such as a throat infection)**. The symptoms include fever, arthritis affecting large joints, and sometimes cardiac involvement, which fits the presentation of the boy.\r\n\r\nRheumatic heart disease is the result of untreated or inadequately treated rheumatic fever, but the acute presentation here is more indicative of rheumatic fever. Enteric fever (typhoid) would not typically present with joint pain in the manner described. Infective endocarditis usually presents with fever and other signs like heart murmurs, embolic phenomena, and might not be preceded by a respiratory tract infection.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 515.","responses":[{"text":"Rheumatic fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infective endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enteric fever","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12737,"text":"You are evaluating a patient with rheumatic fever. He had carditis at diagnosis but no residual valvular disease at discharge. How long will you advise for secondary prophylaxis?","explanation":"According to the American Heart Association (AHA) guidelines, secondary prophylaxis with antibiotics for a patient who had rheumatic fever with carditis but no residual valvular disease should continue for **10 years or until the patient is 21 years of age**, whichever is longer.\r\n\r\nShorter durations of prophylaxis may not provide adequate protection against recurrent attacks of rheumatic fever and potential cardiac involvement.","reference":"Cardiology module; Pediatrics lecture slides; Topic: Rheumatic fever; Sub-topic: Duration of prophylaxis for people who have had acute rheumatic fever.","responses":[{"text":"10 years or till 40 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No need of prophylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12738,"text":"A 10-year-old boy has a history of fever, joint swelling, rash, and new-onset murmur. His anti-streptolysin O titer (ASOT) is raised along with raised ESR. Which of the following is likely to be present in his recent medical history?","explanation":"The most likely recent medical history for this 10-year-old boy with fever, joint swelling, rash, new-onset murmur, elevated ASOT, and ESR is a **history of pharyngitis**. The symptoms and lab findings suggest **rheumatic fever,** a post-infectious complication commonly triggered by **group A streptococcal pharyngitis**. Elevated ASOT levels are indicative of a recent streptococcal infection.\r\n\r\nHistory of skin infection, chickenpox, COVID-19 infection, and measles are less likely to be associated with the presentation of rheumatic fever and the elevated ASOT and ESR levels seen in this case. Rheumatic fever is specifically linked to group A streptococcal infections, most commonly pharyngitis.","reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 79.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 516.","responses":[{"text":"History of pharyngitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"History of chickenpox","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of skin infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of COVID-19 infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of measles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12739,"text":"A 12-year-old girl has been found to have mitral valve regurgitation on an echocardiogram. She is suspected to have rheumatic heart disease. To confirm the diagnosis clinically, Jones criteria is used. Which of the following is not true for the modified Jones criteria?","explanation":"In the modified Jones criteria, **fever** is considered a **minor criterion**, not a major one.\r\n\r\nCarditis, erythema marginatum, and chorea are major criteria, while a prolonged PR interval on an ECG is a minor criterion. These criteria are used in the diagnosis of rheumatic fever, which can subsequently lead to rheumatic heart disease if not managed appropriately.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 516.","responses":[{"text":"Chorea is a major criterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythema marginatum is a major criterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carditis is a major criterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolong PR interval is a minor criterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fever is a major criterion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13001,"text":"A 45-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of typical chest pain radiating to her left arm associated with vomiting for the past three hours. She has a habit of smoking. Her vitals show a blood pressure of 130/70 mmHg and a regular pulse of 130 beats per minute. The systemic examination is remarkable. Her electrocardiogram(ECG) showed an ST-segment elevation in inferior ECG leads. What would be the most appropriate test for this patient?","explanation":"The most appropriate test for this 45-year-old woman presenting with typical chest pain, vomiting, and ST-segment elevation in inferior ECG leads is **coronary angiography**. Given the clinical presentation and ECG changes, she is likely experiencing an **ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI)**. Immediate coronary angiography is the gold standard for both diagnosis and potentially immediate treatment via percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI).\r\n\r\nExercise tolerance test, dobutamine stress echocardiography, nuclear imaging, and trans-thoracic echocardiography are not appropriate for the acute management of a patient with a likely STEMI. These tests are generally used for assessing chronic coronary artery disease or for risk stratification but are not suitable for immediate diagnosis and treatment in the setting of acute chest pain with ST-segment elevation.","reference":"de Bliek EC. ST elevation: Differential diagnosis and caveats. A comprehensive review to help distinguish ST elevation myocardial infarction from nonischemic etiologies of ST elevation. Turkish Journal of Emergency Medicine. Published February 17, 2018. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6009807/","responses":[{"text":"Coronary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trans-thoracic echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dobutamine stress echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise tolerance test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear imaging","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13312,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect for an incised wound?","explanation":"An **incised wound** is a cut that is longer than it is deep, usually resulting from a sharp-edged object such as a knife, razor, or glass.\r\n\r\nDue to the sharp nature of the weapon or object causing an incised wound, the **edges of the wound are usually clean** and straight, as opposed to the more ragged or irregular edges seen in lacerations or other wound types.\r\n\r\nWhile many incised wounds can be painful due to damage to the skin and underlying tissues, the level of pain experienced can vary depending on factors like the location of the wound, depth, individual pain tolerance, and whether or not any nerves were affected. For instance, wounds that are superficial or that do not involve many nerve endings might not be painful.\r\n\r\nIncised wounds can lead to significant blood loss because of their typically clean and straight nature, which does not encourage immediate blood clotting as might be seen with more jagged wounds.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"A wound with clean edges","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It Is always painful","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is always caused by a sharp weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The maximum measurement of an incised wound is its length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeds profusely","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14240,"text":"A 55-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of chest pain. An ECG shows ST-segment elevations in leads II, III, avF, V4, V5, and V6. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for this patient is **inferolateral myocardial infarction (MI)**. ST-segment elevations in leads **II, III, avF** (which represent the inferior wall of the heart), along with elevations in **V4, V5, and V6** (lateral wall), point to an infarction affecting both the inferior and lateral regions of the heart.\r\n\r\nAnterolateral MI would typically involve leads V1-V6, I, aVL, but not II, III, avF. Posterior wall MI often presents with ST-segment depression in the anterior leads (V1-V3) rather than elevation. Anteroseptal MI would primarily involve leads V1-V4, and an inferior wall MI would generally show changes in leads II, III, and avF but not the lateral leads.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Anterolateral MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteroseptal MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior wall MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior wall MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferolateral MI","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14269,"text":"A 35-year-old male patient with a fever and pleuritic chest pain present to the emergency department. His ECG shows diffuse ST elevations and PR depression. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine 24th edition, page 476 figure 16.99","responses":[{"text":"Acute myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HOCM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14322,"text":"A 27-year-old woman presents with intermittent palpitations and dizziness. Her EKG shows a fixed but prolonged PR interval and a dropped beat after every 2 QRS complexes. Which abnormal rhythm is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 410-11, figure 16.33","responses":[{"text":"Mobitz type 1 block","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mobitz type 2 block","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1st degree AV block","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd degree AV block","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bundle branch block","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14328,"text":"What is the pathophysiology behind capillary leak in heart failure?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537065/","responses":[{"text":"Capillary oncotic pressure and hydrostatic pressure act in same direction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillary oncotic pressure is greater than hydrostatic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillary hydrostatic pressure is equal to oncotic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillary oncotic pressure is reduced","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillary hydrostatic pressure is greater than oncotic pressure","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14372,"text":"A 52-year-old male patient presents with sharp chest pain for the last 2 hours. An EKG reveals ST elevations in the inferior wall leads, and the patient's vitals show a BP of 90/55mmHg and a heart rate of 45/min. What is the treatment of choice for this patient's bradycardia?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Davidson's medicine 24th edition, page 434\r\n\r\n(2) https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.166558","responses":[{"text":"DC cardioversion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transvenous pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atropine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Defibrillation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14373,"text":"A 40-year-old female patient presents to the emergency department with a blood pressure of 200/120 mmHg and symptoms of headache and shortness of breath. The patient is otherwise stable and has no signs and symptoms of any systemic involvement. Fundoscopy is unremarkable. What is the appropriate diagnosis in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8522630/#:~:text=Abstract,of%20acute%20target%20organ%20disease.","responses":[{"text":"Isolated systolic hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive urgency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive emergency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preeclampsia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eclampsia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14560,"text":"Which one of these is the best pharmacological treatment for HOCM?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 474","responses":[{"text":"Dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACE inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14651,"text":"A 25-year-old male presents to the emergency department after participating in a strenuous outdoor workout on a hot and humid summer day. He reports feeling dizzy and weak and has a fever of 105.9°F. He is confused, has hot, dry skin, and a rapid heartbeat. The patient's rectal temperature is 40.6°C. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 254-255","responses":[{"text":"Exertional hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heat stroke","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant hyperthermia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heat exhaustion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal body response","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14653,"text":"A 65-year-old female presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of chest pain and shortness of breath. She reports no history of cardiac disease but mentions that her husband passed away 2 days back. An ECG and cardiac enzymes are normal, but an echocardiogram shows a reversible systolic dysfunction of the left ventricular apex. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 475","responses":[{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Takotsubo cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14670,"text":"A 65-year-old male patient with a history of atrial fibrillation and previous DVT presents to the emergency department with a complaint of easy bruising and hematomas on his lower extremities. The patient reports taking warfarin as prescribed by his primary care physician for the past three months. His INR is found to be elevated at 7.8 and he has active bleeding from a small laceration on his leg. The patient reports no recent changes in his diet or medication regimen. The patient's blood pressure is stable, but he has a decreased hemoglobin level of 8g/dL. What is the initial therapeutic step?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th edition, page 950","responses":[{"text":"Packed red cell transfusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV vitamin K","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fresh frozen plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recombinant factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whole blood transfusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14711,"text":"A 55-year-old male presents to the clinic with a complaint of chest pain and shortness of breath. He reports a history of hypertension and a family history of sudden cardiac death (SCD). Physical examination reveals a systolic ejection murmur and left ventricular septal hypertrophy on echocardiography. Which of these interventions will most likely prevent SCD in this patient?","explanation":"The most likely intervention to prevent **sudden cardiac death (SCD)** in this 55-year-old male with a history of hypertension, family history of SCD, systolic ejection murmur, and left ventricular septal hypertrophy on echocardiography is an **implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD)**. ICDs are the definitive treatment for preventing SCD in individuals with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and a high risk for ventricular arrhythmias.\r\n\r\nCardiac transplant is a drastic measure and not the first line of defense for preventing SCD. Pacemakers and biventricular synchronization therapy are more appropriate for heart failure or specific arrhythmias but are not the best options for preventing SCD in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. Digoxin is used for rate control in conditions like atrial fibrillation but does not prevent SCD.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 423.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiac transplant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biventricular synchronization therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pacemaker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14833,"text":"A 24-year-old male presents to the emergency with chest pain and shortness of breath for the last 24 hours. He says it has worsened rapidly and is now even present at a rest. Past history is unremarkable except for an upper respiratory tract infection 4 days ago. An urgent EKG is performed which is unremarkable. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for this 24-year-old male with **chest pain** and shortness of breath following a recent upper respiratory tract infection is **myocarditis**. Myocarditis often follows a **viral infection** and can present with symptoms mimicking a heart attack but with an **unremarkable EKG**.\r\n\r\nUnstable angina, NSTEMI, and STEMI are less likely in a young, otherwise healthy individual with a preceding upper respiratory tract infection. Pleuritis would typically not worsen rapidly and cause shortness of breath to the extent described.","reference":"Davidson's medicine, 24th ed, page 472","responses":[{"text":"Unstable angina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleuritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NSTEMI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"STEMI","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14937,"text":"Which one of these treatment options is the first line for mitral stenosis with significant symptoms?","explanation":"The **first-line treatment** for mitral stenosis with significant symptoms is **balloon valvuloplasty**. This procedure involves inflating a balloon within the mitral valve to separate the valve leaflets and relieve the obstruction, improving blood flow.\r\n\r\nOpen commissurotomy and valve replacement are generally reserved for more severe or refractory cases. A heart transplant is not the first-line treatment and is usually considered a last resort for severe heart failure not responsive to other treatments. \"No management needed\" is incorrect as significant symptoms necessitate intervention.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Valve replacement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open commissurotomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart transplant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No management needed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Balloon valvuloplasty","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14941,"text":"A 23-year-old primigravida, at 28 weeks of gestation, presents with shortness of breath. On examination, she has a loud S1 and an erratic pulse. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for a 23-year-old primigravida at 28 weeks of gestation with **shortness of breath, a loud S1**, and an **erratic pulse** is mitral stenosis. The condition can become symptomatic or worsen during pregnancy due to increased circulatory demands and often presents with a loud S1 and arrhythmias like atrial fibrillation, which would account for the erratic pulse.\r\n\r\nMitral regurgitation typically presents with a soft S1 and does not usually cause an erratic pulse. Mild anemia, while common in pregnancy, would not usually produce a loud S1 or erratic pulse. A normal pregnancy would not produce the severe symptoms described. Dilated cardiomyopathy would not typically present with a loud S1.","reference":"(1).Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 454\r\n\r\n(2) Nesheiwat Z, Goyal A, Jagtap M. Atrial fibrillation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 27, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526072/","responses":[{"text":"Normal pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17421,"text":"Which of the following drugs is given sublingually to relieve the pain of angina pectoris?","explanation":"The drug given **sublingually** to relieve the pain of angina pectoris is **glyceryl trinitrate (also known as nitroglycerin)**. This medication acts quickly when taken sublingually and is effective in dilating coronary arteries and improving blood flow to the heart muscle, thereby alleviating angina pain.\r\n\r\nSodium nitrate is not used for treating angina. Nifedipine is a calcium channel blocker used mainly for hypertension and chronic stable angina but is not typically given sublingually for immediate angina relief. Propranolol is a beta-blocker used for long-term management of angina and other cardiovascular conditions but is not used for immediate relief of acute angina symptoms.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 201-202.","responses":[{"text":"Nifedipine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium nitrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glyceryl trinitrate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":17423,"text":"Which drug will be given for acute treatment of angina?","explanation":"For the acute treatment of angina, **glyceryl trinitrate** (also known as nitroglycerin) is commonly used. This medication works by relaxing the smooth muscle in blood vessel walls, leading to **dilation of the coronary arteries**, which in turn increases the supply of blood and oxygen to the heart muscle.\r\n\r\nIn the context of acute angina, propranolol, verapamil, and nifedipine are generally not the first choices for immediate relief. Propranolol is a beta-blocker and verapamil is a calcium channel blocker; both are more commonly used for the long-term management of angina. Nifedipine is also a calcium channel blocker but is generally not used in the acute setting due to its potential to cause a reflex tachycardia.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Nifedipine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Verapamil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glyceryl trinitrate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17424,"text":"Which antihypertensive is used topically to treat alopecia areata?","explanation":"**Minoxidil** is the antihypertensive medication that is also used topically to treat **alopecia areata**. Originally developed as an oral medication for hypertension, it was discovered to have the side effect of hair growth. This led to the development of a topical formulation specifically for the treatment of alopecia.\r\n\r\nPrazosin, hydralazine, and captopril are all antihypertensive medications but are not used for the treatment of alopecia areata. None of these options have a topical formulation approved for such use.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 581.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Minoxidil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17425,"text":"Which antihypertensive can cause rebound hypertension on sudden discontinuation?","explanation":"**Clonidine** is the antihypertensive medication that can cause **rebound hypertension** upon sudden discontinuation. This is because clonidine is a centrally acting alpha-2 adrenergic agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow, leading to lower blood pressure. Sudden withdrawal of the drug can lead to a **sudden increase in sympathetic activity**, resulting in a rapid and potentially dangerous increase in blood pressure.\r\n\r\nLosartan is an angiotensin II receptor blocker and generally does not cause rebound hypertension upon discontinuation. Chlorothiazide is a diuretic, and while sudden discontinuation might lead to a return of hypertension, it is generally not associated with rebound hypertension. Prazosin, an alpha-1 receptor blocker, also is not generally associated with rebound hypertension upon discontinuation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Clonidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Losartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17426,"text":"Which coagulation factor falls most rapidly after starting warfarin?","explanation":"The coagulation factor that falls most rapidly after starting warfarin is **factor VII**. **Warfarin** inhibits the synthesis of vitamin K-dependent coagulation factors, including II (Prothrombin), VII, IX, and X. Among these, factor VII has the **shortest half-life**, and thus, its levels drop most quickly when warfarin therapy is initiated.\r\n\r\nOther factors like prothrombin (factor II), factor IX, and factor X also decrease, but they have longer half-lives compared to factor VII, so their levels do not fall as rapidly. Factor XI is not a vitamin K-dependent coagulation factor, so its levels are not directly affected by warfarin.","reference":"Shikdar S, Vashisht R, Bhattacharya PT. International normalized ratio(Inr). In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 15, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507707/","responses":[{"text":"Factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17989,"text":"Which of the following is the most common indication for coronary artery bypass graft (CABG)?","explanation":"The most common indication for **coronary artery bypass graft (CABG)** is **multivessel disease**. In patients with multivessel coronary artery disease, CABG is often recommended to improve blood flow to the myocardium and reduce the risk of myocardial infarction.\r\n\r\nHeart failure is generally not the primary indication for CABG; rather, it would be managed with medication and other therapies first. Valvular defects are typically not addressed through CABG; instead, they require valve repair or replacement procedures. A 20% or greater stenosis of the right coronary artery (RCA) or 50% or less stenosis of the left coronary artery (LCA) would usually not be severe enough to necessitate CABG. Medical management or percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) are more commonly employed for lesser degrees of stenosis.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 492.\r\n\r\n(2) Bachar BJ, Manna B. Coronary artery bypass graft. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507836/","responses":[{"text":"20% or greater stenosis of right coronary artery (RCA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50% or less than 50% stenosis of left coronary artery (LCA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multivessel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Valvular defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17990,"text":"A child has been cyanotic since birth. He has pulmonary edema and shortness of breath but no signs of congestive cardiac failure are found. Which of the following associated abnormalities would he have?","explanation":"In a cyanotic child with **pulmonary edema** and **shortness of breath** but without signs of congestive cardiac failure, **clubbing** would be the most likely associated abnormality. Clubbing is a common feature in chronic hypoxia, which may be present in cyanotic heart conditions.\r\n\r\nIncreased blood pressure is generally not associated with cyanotic congenital heart diseases. Severe anemia would exacerbate cyanosis but is not a direct result of the heart condition. Pretibial edema is usually a sign of cardiac failure, which is not present in this case.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 532.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pretibial edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clubbing","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":17991,"text":"Aspirin causes increased bleeding time by which of the following mechanisms?","explanation":"Aspirin causes increased bleeding time by **inhibiting thromboxane A2 synthesis** in platelets. Thromboxane A2 is essential for platelet aggregation, so its inhibition leads to **impaired platelet function** and **prolonged bleeding time**. \r\n\r\nInhibiting clotting factors, inhibiting antithrombin III, and inhibiting prostacyclin release from endothelial cells are not the mechanisms by which aspirin increases bleeding time.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibits thromboxane A2 synthesis in platelets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits clotting factors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits prostacyclin release from endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17992,"text":"Which of the following is an adverse side effect of fibrinolytic therapy?","explanation":"**Fibrinolytic therapy** aims to break down clots but also carries a risk of causing bleeding, including potentially **life-threatening intracranial hemorrhage**.\r\n\r\nPulmonary embolism, deep vein thrombosis, and formation of antiplatelet antibodies are not typically caused by fibrinolytic therapy; in fact, these agents may be used to treat embolism or thrombosis. Hypertension is also not a known adverse effect of fibrinolytic therapy.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Acute hemorrhagic stroke","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep vein thrombosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of antiplatelet antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17993,"text":"A child presents to the clinic with a complaint of repeated infections and pneumonia since birth. On examination, a systolic murmur is heard at the left 4th intercostal space, and biventricular hypertrophy is found on imaging. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 460.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of the great arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17994,"text":"Gastric lavage is absolutely contraindicated in which of the following situations?","explanation":"**Gastric lavage** is contraindicated in cases of **corrosive substance** ingestion, such as **sulphuric acid**, because it can exacerbate the chemical injury to the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nFor the incorrect options: With strychnine or carbolic acid poisoning, gastric lavage might still be considered based on the specific clinical circumstances. Gastric lavage is not typically recommended after four to six hours post-ingestion unless the substance has delayed gastrointestinal absorption. For volatile poisonings, gastric lavage is not generally effective and can lead to rapid evaporation and inhalation of the toxic fumes, but it is not considered absolutely contraindicated like in the case of corrosive substances.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 474.","responses":[{"text":"When patient comes with sulphuric acid poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient comes with volatile poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient comes after four to six hours of poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient has poisoning with carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"When patient comes with strychnine poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17995,"text":"An infant born at term is noted to have cyanosis during the first week of life. On examination, a heart murmur is auscultated. Investigations show an overriding aorta, ventricular septal defect, right ventricular thickening, and pulmonic stenosis. This infant is most likely to have which congenital anomaly?","explanation":"The findings of an **overriding aorta, ventricular septal defect, right ventricular hypertrophy**, and **pulmonic stenosis** are classic components of **tetralogy of Fallot**, a common cyanotic congenital heart defect.\r\n\r\nAtrial septal defect usually does not cause cyanosis in infancy. Ventricular septal defect may cause heart failure but usually not cyanosis unless it is part of another complex defect like tetralogy of Fallot. Persistent truncus arteriosus usually presents with early-onset heart failure and does not typically feature the same set of abnormalities seen here.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 538.","responses":[{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent truncus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17996,"text":"A 54-year-old female presents to the emergency with shortness of breath for 4 months and is unable to perform her daily activities. She has a history of hyperlipidemia, diabetes, and three-vessel coronary artery disease for about 4 years. On examination, bilateral crepitations/crackles are present in the lungs. What is the diagnosis of her condition?","explanation":"The patient's shortness of breath, inability to perform daily activities, history of coronary artery disease, hyperlipidemia, and diabetes, as well as the presence of bilateral lung crepitations or crackles on examination, are indicative of **left-sided heart failure**.\r\n\r\nMyocarditis usually has an acute presentation and may include fever. Endocarditis would likely present with signs of infection, such as fever, and possibly embolic phenomena. Right heart failure would typically present with peripheral edema and jugular venous distension rather than lung crackles.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 534.","responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17997,"text":"A 60-year-old patient presents to the clinic with crushing chest pain radiating to the left arm. He is given sublingual nitroglycerin but it does not improve his condition. If the pain lasts for \u003e20 minutes it is more likely to be which of the following conditions?","explanation":"TIf the crushing chest pain radiating to the left arm lasts for more than 20 minutes and is unresponsive to nitroglycerin, it is highly suggestive of a **myocardial infarction (MI)**, a serious medical condition requiring immediate attention. \r\n\r\nAcute coronary syndrome is a broader term that encompasses a range of conditions including unstable angina and myocardial infarction. However, the prolonged pain unresponsive to nitroglycerin makes myocardial infarction the more likely diagnosis. Myocarditis typically presents differently and may include symptoms like fever and malaise. Left heart failure and congestive heart failure usually present with additional symptoms like shortness of breath, fatigue, and fluid retention, rather than isolated chest pain.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 73.","responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute coronary syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17998,"text":"A patient presents to the clinic with chest pain and is diagnosed with angina pectoris. Which of the following cells sustain the initial injury due to angina pectoris resulting from arterial disease?","explanation":"In angina pectoris resulting from arterial disease, **endothelial cells** lining the coronary arteries are the initial cells to sustain injury. Dysfunction or injury to endothelial cells can result in impaired vasodilation, increased platelet adhesion, and a pro-inflammatory state, all of which contribute to angina.\r\n\r\nNeutrophils, platelets, and monocytes are components of the immune and coagulation systems and play a role in the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis and its complications but are not the initial cells to sustain injury in angina pectoris.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 68, 73.","responses":[{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17999,"text":"A 28-year-old male, with a known case of hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy, presents in the cardiac emergency room with a complaint of recurrent syncope. His elder brother died at the age of 30 years. Which of the following is the definite treatment that can prevent sudden cardiac death in this patient?","explanation":"For patients with **hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy** who have risk factors for sudden cardiac death (SCD), such as a family history of sudden cardiac death and recurrent syncope, the definitive treatment to prevent SCD is the placement of an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD).\r\n\r\nSeptal ablation is a treatment for hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy but does not specifically prevent sudden cardiac death. Reassurance is not adequate for someone with this condition and symptoms. Dual chamber pacing has been explored as a treatment option but is not definitive for preventing sudden cardiac death. Beta blockers are often used for symptom relief but are not definitive in preventing sudden cardiac death in high-risk individuals.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 540.","responses":[{"text":"Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dual chamber pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reassurance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septal ablation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18000,"text":"High-dose long-term use of hydralazine causes which of the following effects?","explanation":"Long-term use of **hydralazine**, especially at high doses, is associated with **drug-induced lupus erythematosus**, which can present with symptoms such as joint pain, skin rash, and fever.\r\n\r\nThrombocytopenia is not typically associated with hydralazine. Gynecomastia is more commonly linked with spironolactone. Hemolytic anemia is not generally caused by hydralazine. Agranulocytosis is rare and not specifically associated with high-dose long-term hydralazine use.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 214-215.","responses":[{"text":"Agranulocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gynecomastia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lupus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18007,"text":"A researcher is conducting a study in which he will be following COVID-19 patients (both men and women) to find the long term complications of coronavirus. What type of study is this?","explanation":"In a **cohort study**, a group of individuals with a certain exposure (in this case, COVID-19 infection) is followed over time to determine the incidence and risk factors for certain outcomes, such as long-term complications.\r\n\r\nA systematic review synthesizes multiple studies on a specific question but does not involve primary data collection. \r\n\r\nA case report focuses on a single patient's medical history, symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, and outcome. \r\n\r\nA case-control study compares those with a specific condition to those without, often looking back in time.","reference":"Andrade C. Research design: cohort studies. Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine. Published March 2022. Accessed August 15, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9120971/","responses":[{"text":"Cohort","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Systematic review","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case control","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18008,"text":"What is the process by which one activates and sustains thoughts, behavior, and emotions, in order to reach his goal?","explanation":"**Self-regulation** refers to the process of controlling one's behavior, emotions, and thoughts in the pursuit of long-term goals. It involves activating, monitoring, and maintaining various cognitive, emotional, and behavioral faculties to achieve desired outcomes.\r\n\r\nSelf-esteem refers to one's overall sense of self-worth but does not specifically pertain to goal-directed behavior. Self-perception is how one views oneself, but it does not necessarily involve the active process of reaching goals. Self-awareness involves understanding one's own emotions and behaviors but is not specifically about goal-directed activity. Self ideas is not a term commonly associated with the process of achieving goals.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Cardiology Module, Behavioral science, Topic: Learning about the Self.","responses":[{"text":"Self perception","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self awareness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self ideas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self esteem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self regulation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18010,"text":"Which factor influences self-regulation?","explanation":"**Self-regulation** is largely influenced by **self-awareness**, which includes the ability to recognize one's emotions, thoughts, and actions. Being aware of oneself allows for better management of behavior and makes it easier to adapt to varying situations.\r\n\r\nLow motivation is generally a hindrance to self-regulation rather than an influence that promotes it. Communication is not directly responsible for an individual's ability to self-regulate. Gratification is an outcome or a goal but does not influence self-regulation directly. Self-perception may be related, but it is self-awareness that has a more direct role in influencing self-regulation.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Behavioral science, Topic: Learning about the self.","responses":[{"text":"Low motivation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self perception","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gratification","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Communication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self awareness (knowledge)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18011,"text":"What is the purpose of screening questions in a research questionnaire?","explanation":"**Screening questions** are used in a research questionnaire to **filter out participants** who do not meet the criteria for the study. This ensures that the sample population is suitable for the research objectives.\r\n\r\nMinimizing the sample size is not the primary goal of screening questions; their goal is to identify suitable participants. Efficient use of time might be a byproduct but is not the main objective. Diagnosis of disease is not the purpose of screening questions in research; rather, they're used to see if participants meet the study criteria.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Research, Topic: Designing the questionnaire.","responses":[{"text":"Exclude out certain individuals","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Minimize sample size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diagnosis of disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manage time efficiently","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18013,"text":"What brings bias to the research questionnaire?","explanation":"**Leading questions** are questions are designed in a way that prompts or encourages the respondent to answer in a particular manner, thereby introducing **bias** into the research. \r\n\r\n\"Sensitive questions\" may affect the respondent's comfort level but don't necessarily introduce bias. \"Open-ended questions\" can actually be less biased because they allow respondents to freely express their views. \"Skip pattern in questions\" refers to the logical flow of a questionnaire and does not inherently introduce bias.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Research, Topic: Designing the questionnaire.","responses":[{"text":"Leading questions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensitive questions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open-ended questions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skip pattern in questions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18014,"text":"A professor asks his students to code all the data that is being collected. What is its significance?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Research, Topic: Designing the questionnaire.\r\n\r\n(2) Stone DH. Design a questionnaire. BMJ. 1993;307(6914):1264-1266. Accessed August 15, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1679392/","responses":[{"text":"Delayed data entry","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Errors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fast data analysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduces efficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases efficiency","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18015,"text":"What are the right ventricular changes seen in acute cor pulmonale?","explanation":"**Acute cor pulmonale** typically presents with sudden **right ventricular dilatation** in response to a rapid rise in pulmonary artery pressure, which may be caused by conditions such as a massive pulmonary embolism. Hypertrophy (thickening of the cardiac muscle) usually takes time to develop and is generally not seen in acute situations.\r\n\r\nRight ventricular dilatation with hypertrophy and right ventricular hypertrophy are more likely to be seen in chronic cor pulmonale. Right ventricular dilatation with fibrosis would typically be a long-term change rather than an acute event.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 556.","responses":[{"text":"Right ventricular dilatation with hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular dilatation without hypertrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricular dilatation with fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18016,"text":"Which of the following is a branch of the left coronary artery that runs in the interventricular septum?","explanation":"**Anterior interventricular artery**, also known as the left anterior descending (LAD) artery, is a branch of the **left coronary artery** and runs down the anterior interventricular groove, supplying the **interventricular septum** and the anterior wall of the left ventricle.\r\n\r\nThe posterior interventricular artery and posterior descending artery are usually branches of the right coronary artery and run in the posterior interventricular groove. The left circumflex artery is another branch of the left coronary artery but circles around the left side of the heart, running in the coronary sulcus.","reference":"(1) Rehman I, Kerndt CC, Rehman A. Anatomy, thorax, heart left anterior descending (Lad) artery. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed August 15, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482375/\r\n\r\n(2) Left anterior descending artery (Lad). Kenhub. Accessed August 15, 2023. https://www.kenhub.com/en/library/anatomy/left-anterior-descending-artery-lad","responses":[{"text":"Left circumflex artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior interventricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior interventricular artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior descending artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18017,"text":"A 53-year-old obese male comes to the clinic with complaints of recurrent chest pain. He has experienced similar chest pains for the past few years. He also experiences cramps while walking. His blood glucose level is 170 mg/dl and his cholesterol level is 358 mg/dl. His ECG and cardiac markers are normal. What is the underlying pathology of this condition?","explanation":"The patient's history of recurrent chest pain, cramps while walking, elevated blood glucose, and high cholesterol levels strongly suggest **atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease**. Atherosclerosis is a condition in which plaque builds up inside the arteries, and in this case, it is affecting the coronary arteries, which supply the heart muscle. Although he has symptoms of chest pain, the normal ECG and cardiac markers rule out acute myocardial infarction or plaque rupture at this time.\r\n\r\nICongestive heart failure primarily presents with symptoms like fluid retention, breathlessness, and fatigue; it would not account for the cramps while walking or the elevated glucose and cholesterol levels seen here. Atherosclerotic plaque rupture would result in abnormal cardiac markers, which are normal in this case. Vasospasm of the coronary artery could cause chest pain, but it would not explain the cramps while walking or the high cholesterol and glucose levels.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Atherosclerosis of coronary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasospasm of coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atherosclerotic plaque rupture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18018,"text":"A child is found to have a defect at the limbus of foramen ovale during an annual checkup. What can be the possible structure involved?","explanation":"The **foramen ovale** is a hole in the atrial septum that normally exists during fetal life and usually closes shortly after birth. When this hole does not close completely, an **atrial septal defect (ASD)** occurs. **Secundum atrial septal defects** are the most common type of ASDs and are located at the site of the foramen ovale, near the limbus (the rim or border).\r\n\r\nA ventricular septal defect is a hole in the ventricular septum and is not related to the foramen ovale. Primum atrial septal defect is located at the lower part of the atrial septum and is associated with abnormalities of the atrioventricular valves, but not at the site of the foramen ovale. A valvular defect would imply a problem with one of the heart valves, which is not the underlying diagnosis in this child.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 537.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valvular defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secundum atrial septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primum atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18019,"text":"An elderly person with a known history of hypertension presents to the clinic. He informs that he has been taking 50 mg hydrochlorothiazide for a while but it no longer helps in reducing blood pressure. He is given another medicine and a spontaneous fall in systolic blood pressure is seen. What is the medication?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 513-514.","responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Losartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha methyldopa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amlodipine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18020,"text":"At which costal cartilage level, the aortic valve is present?","explanation":null,"reference":"Halliday NL, Chung HM. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 9th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 75.","responses":[{"text":"Left 5th intercostal space (ICS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right 4th intercostal space (ICS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left 3rd intercostal space (ICS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left 4th intercostal space (ICS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right 2nd intercostal space (ICS)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18021,"text":"Physical activity in healthy and fit individuals reduces the risk of cardiovascular disease by what percentage?","explanation":"Numerous studies have shown that regular **physical activity** can reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease by approximately **30%.** This includes a range of cardiovascular conditions such as coronary artery disease, hypertension, and stroke.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Community-medicine, Topic: Role of diet and nutritional lifestyle modification.","responses":[{"text":"100%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18022,"text":"What are the types of antidotes which act by forming new less toxic compounds after combining with poison?","explanation":"**Chemical antidotes** act by forming a new, less toxic compound when they combine with the poison. This **neutralizes** the poisonous substance, making it **less harmful** to the body.\r\n\r\nPhysical antidotes work by physically removing the poison, such as activated charcoal adsorbing a substance in the gut. Universal antidotes are a theoretical concept and do not exist in practice for all types of poison. Physiological antidotes act by counteracting the physiological effects of the poison but do not change the chemical structure of the poison.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Cardiology module, Forensic medicine, Topic: General toxicology II.","responses":[{"text":"Physiological antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical antidotes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Universal antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18023,"text":"Which drug decreases mortality in ST-elevation myocardial infarction?","explanation":"**Aspirin** is an antiplatelet drug that has been shown to significantly decrease mortality in patients with **ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI)** when given promptly.\r\n\r\nNitroglycerin can alleviate angina but has not been shown to reduce mortality in STEMI. Beta blockers are used for rate control and to improve symptoms but are not proven to significantly reduce immediate mortality in the acute phase of STEMI. Oxygen is generally administered to maintain adequate oxygenation but does not directly decrease mortality in STEMI. Anticoagulation with heparin is commonly used in the management of STEMI to prevent thrombotic complications, but it does not directly reduce mortality as effectively as aspirin.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 272.","responses":[{"text":"Aspirin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitroglycerin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anticoagulation with heparin","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

